 "invariants": {
  "dsl_code": "    # -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# RCC Bowtie \u2014 package config + global wiring\n#\n# This `arch.neuro` is the architecture's entry point. It sets runtime\n# defaults, declares the 7 classical neurotransmitter systems globally,\n# pulls in every brain-region module via `import`, then defines the\n# cross-module synaptic wiring + neuromodulator routing.\n#\n# Per-region module files live under modules/; they declare populations\n# and (optionally) their local internal wiring. Shared mechanics live\n# under lib/.\n#\n# Topology: bowtie with re-entry (sensory \u2192 thalamus \u2192 GWS \u2192 PFC \u2192 ...\n# \u2192 thalamus). IIT 4.0 compliant (every part has both causes and effects\n# in the system \u2192 \u03a6 > 0).\n#\n# References \u2014 Dehaene (2011), Baars (2005), Doya (1999), Tononi (2016),\n# Mashour (2020).\n\n# Equations are imported from lib/equations.neuro (see MODULE IMPORTS below).\n# This keeps arch.neuro free of implementation details and focuses it on\n# high-level architecture + wiring + constraints.\n\narchitecture rcc_bowtie {\n    d_sem: 256,\n    dt: 0.01\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# TRAINING \u2014 pipeline behavior the BRIAN harness applies on top of the\n# compiled DSL circuit. Loss clipping here is the declarative form of the\n# p4 architectural fix (was: cfg.loss_clip_robust=True, factor=3.0).\n# =============================================================================\n\ntraining {\n    # MAT-phase-gated mechanisms + declarative early-exit pass marks.\n    # `preset` sets the trunk dims (overrides env PRESET when set).\n    # See docs/OOD_PUSH_STAGES.md + docs/metrics.md.\n    preset:        \"rcc_bowtie_30m_p4\"\n    loss_clipping: { enabled: true, method: \"per_sample\", factor: 3.0 }\n    quantization:  { enabled: false, bits: 8 }\n    optimizer:     \"adamw\"\n    learning_rate: 0.0005      # was 3e-4 \u2014 pushed up after fair-fight run\n                                # showed lots of headroom (gnorm stable at\n                                # 1-2, no instability); 5e-4 is GPT-2-medium-class\n    # \u2554\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2557\n    # \u2551  PRETRAIN-FRIENDLY RECIPE  (Jun 2026 surgery)                \u2551\n    # \u2551                                                              \u2551\n    # \u2551  The previous values (wd=0.12 dropout=0.12 llrd=0.85         \u2551\n    # \u2551  flooding=4.0 label_smooth=0.05) were tuned to NARROW the    \u2551\n    # \u2551  train\u2192WikiText OOD gap after ~10k steps of an already-      \u2551\n    # \u2551  pretrained checkpoint. Applied from-scratch they suppress   \u2551\n    # \u2551  early learning catastrophically:                            \u2551\n    # \u2551    \u2022 flooding=4.0 hard-caps train ppl at \u224855 \u2014 model is      \u2551\n    # \u2551      contractually forbidden from improving below ln(55)\u22484   \u2551\n    # \u2551    \u2022 LLRD=0.85 over 8 depth + adapters (~170 groups) starves \u2551\n    # \u2551      bottom layers at 0.85^20 \u2248 4% of base LR                \u2551\n    # \u2551    \u2022 dropout=0.12 + wd=0.12 are anti-regularisers when the   \u2551\n    # \u2551      model is severely under-fit (train ppl 500+)            \u2551\n    # \u2551                                                              \u2551\n    # \u2551  New values are GPT-2 / LLaMA pretraining defaults. Once the \u2551\n    # \u2551  trunk reaches its capacity ceiling (train ppl < ~30), the   \u2551\n    # \u2551  OOD-narrowing knobs can be re-enabled via the PR2           \u2551\n    # \u2551  regularization controller (DAR/PCC/iso/CMD) which is        \u2551\n    # \u2551  designed to compose additively without poisoning early      \u2551\n    # \u2551  training. See docs/PRETRAIN_RECIPE.md.                      \u2551\n    # \u255a\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u255d\n    weight_decay:  0.01        # was 0.12 \u2014 GPT-2/LLaMA use 0.01\u20130.1\n    grad_accum:    8           # was 1 \u2014 batch=4 \u00d7 ctx=2048 \u00d7 accum=8 = 65k\n                                # tok/step (~12% of GPT-2's 524k). Prior\n                                # 8k tok/step caused \u00b135% loss swings from\n                                # micro-batch noise; this kills the jitter\n                                # at zero VRAM cost (one extra fwd+bwd, no\n                                # extra activations stored).\n    grad_clip:     1.0\n    label_smoothing: 0.0       # was 0.05 \u2014 inflates raw PPL, off for pretrain\n    dropout:       0.0         # was 0.12 \u2014 model is under-fit, no overfit yet\n    flooding_level: 0.0        # was 4.0 \u2014 DEATH SENTENCE for pretraining\n    stochastic_depth: 0.0      # was 0.1  \u2014 reduces effective depth\n    z_loss: 0.0001             # keep \u2014 cheap PaLM-style logit stabiliser\n    llrd: 1.0                  # was 0.85 \u2014 LLRD is for FINE-TUNING, not pretrain\n    pct_trunk:     0.0\n    pct_strength:  0.0\n    # \u2500\u2500 HPB Phases 1-5 \u2014 novel-topology mechanisms ACTIVATED \u2500\u2500\n    # All zero-init: first forward is bit-identical to baseline; behaviour\n    # emerges as the gates lift off zero under LM loss. Composable \u2014\n    # H19 monitors surprise (read by H15 for analytics when write_gate\n    # is \"surprise\"; currently \"all\" for the Phase-5 uniform-writes\n    # baseline before the wake/sleep replay loop (Phase 6) lands.\n    #\n    # HPB Phase 1 + Phase 2: H16 multi-scale grid-cell positions.\n    # K=4 scales at \u03c6-ratio (Sargolini 2006; Stensola 2012) \u2014 provable\n    # length-OOD extrapolation. Activates the dormant code path; the\n    # 2K=8 raw features project to d_model via a zero-init head, so the\n    # first forward is bit-identical to baseline (Phase 1 contract).\n    grid_positions: { enabled: true, n_scales: 4, scale_ratio: 1.6180339887, base_period: 16.0 }\n    # HPB Phase 5: H19 local-context surprise head (Mismatch Negativity).\n    # Exposes per-token surprise = nll_local \u2212 nll_global on every\n    # train forward; harness logs it for diagnostics. Composes with\n    # H15's write gate when write_gate = \"surprise\".\n    surprise_head:  { enabled: true, dim: 128, local_window: 64 }\n    # HPB Phase 5: H15 episodic kNN memory (Memorizing Transformers /\n    # RETRO). Uniform writes (write_gate=\"all\") for the Phase-5\n    # baseline; surprise-gating + wake/sleep replay come in Phase 6.\n    # alpha_init=0 \u21d2 ReZero start: first forward bit-identical to\n    # baseline; the value blend only activates as \u03b1 lifts off zero\n    # under LM gradient pressure.\n    episodic_memory: { enabled: true, slots: 4096, k: 32, alpha_init: 0.0,\n                       write_gate: \"all\", write_quantile: 0.8 }\n    # HPB Phase 3 \u2014 Multi-Scale Predictive Coding Cascade.  Applies the\n    # MDRV-VBB free-energy at every adjacent layer pair (\u2113, \u2113+1) of the\n    # trunk, with geometric weight decay \u03bb_\u2113 = base_weight \u00b7 0.5^((L-1)-\u2113)\n    # so the deepest (bowtie waist) pair dominates and the shallowest\n    # pair contributes a small but non-zero compositional regulariser.\n    # Shares all VBB hyperparameters (alpha / free_bits / beta_max / eta).\n    # Composes additively with the single-waist VBB above.\n    mspcc: { enabled: true, base_weight: 0.02, layer_weight_decay: 0.5 }\n    # HPB Phase 4 \u2014 Hyperbolic Bowtie Waist (HBW). Curvature c=1.0 of\n    # the Poincar\u00e9 ball on which the VBB posterior is wrapped. The KL\n    # closed form picks up a Jacobian-log-det correction that strictly\n    # upper-bounds the Euclidean KL for any non-zero \u2016\u03bc\u2016 \u2014 making\n    # \u03c3-collapse harder by the construction of the geometry itself.\n    # Composes with all MDRV stabilisers (free-bits, \u03b2-ceiling, PEC).\n    vbb_curvature: 1.0\n    # \u2500\u2500 Multi-Trunk-v2: thalamic multi-cortex routing (see \u00a75.7) \u2500\u2500\n    # Four specialist language cortices (math / code / chat / general)\n    # mixed per token by neuroslm.cortex.ThalamicRouter.  The router\n    # combines a deterministic lexical-bias prior (`lexical_bias_weight`\n    # added to logits for the matching domain) with a zero-init\n    # learnable head (ReZero contract \u2014 at step 0, routing = pure\n    # lexical), and optionally damps per-batch oscillations through\n    # a BEMA running mean (`bema_tau`).\n    #\n    # Math (per token t in batch sample i, N = #cortices):\n    #     L_{ti} = beta * 1[x_{ti} in D] + W @ phi(x_{ti})\n    #     p_{ti} = softmax(L_{ti})                 in Delta^N\n    #     h_{ti} = sum_n p_{ti,n} * P_n(C_n(x))_{ti}\n    #\n    # At beta = lexical_bias_weight = 2.0 and N = 4 a token in domain\n    # d routes to cortex d with probability  e^2 / (e^2 + 3) ~ 0.730\n    # before any LM gradient lands (verified analytically in\n    # tests/test_ensemble_routing.py::test_pure_math_sequence_*).\n    #\n    # `weights` selects the production sub-cortex backend:\n    #     \"stub\" \u2014 random-init StubSubCortex (cold-start, no download)\n    #     \"gpt2\" \u2014 HuggingFace GPT-2 family, see DEFAULT_GPT2_VARIANTS\n    #              in neuroslm/cortex.py (gpt2-medium for math,\n    #              distilgpt2 for code, gpt2 for chat + general).\n    # `freeze_weights = true` keeps the GPT-2 backbones frozen and\n    # trains only the router + per-cortex projections in the cold-start\n    # phase.  Set to false to fine-tune all cortices end-to-end.\n    #\n    # \u2500\u2500 Mixture-of-Experts (`experts: [...]`) supersedes `weights:` \u2500\u2500\n    # Setting `experts: [...]` replaces the legacy single-`weights`\n    # field with an explicit per-expert roster. Each expert returns\n    # logits DIRECTLY in trunk-vocab space via its OWN pretrained LM\n    # head \u2014 bypassing the random Xavier `cortex_lm_head` projection\n    # that previously sat at the catastrophic `loss \u2248 ln(V)` ceiling\n    # (see scripts/diagnose_cortex_init.py for the in-vitro repro).\n    # When `experts:` is set, `n_cortices` and `domains:` are\n    # auto-derived from the roster (still listed below for human\n    # readability). See neuroslm/experts.py + tests/training/\n    # test_lm_expert_harness_integration.py for the smoking-gun CE\n    # contract (initial CE on natural English drops from ~10.85 to\n    # ~3-5 nats at step 0).\n    multi_cortex: {\n        enabled:             true,\n        n_cortices:          3,\n        domains:             [\"general\", \"code\", \"reasoning\"],\n        # Per-expert roster (new MoE path). Each row binds a HuggingFace\n        # model id to a routing domain. The expert's pretrained LM head\n        # produces trunk-vocab logits directly via VocabBridge \u2014 no\n        # random projection chain, no rogue-dim band-aid LayerNorm.\n        #\n        # 2026-06-14 (H22): the `general` slot was upgraded from `gpt2`\n        # (2019, ~125M params, WebText) to `smollm2_360m` (HuggingFaceTB\n        # /SmolLM2-360M \u2014 late-2024, ~360M params, 4T tokens of curated\n        # FineWeb-Edu + SmolLM-corpus + Cosmopedia). 3\u00d7 the parameters,\n        # ~100\u00d7 the training tokens, dramatically better per-parameter\n        # quality on natural English. Trade-off: SmolLM2 uses its own\n        # tokenizer (~49 152 BPE) \u2260 trunk's gpt2 tokenizer, so the\n        # `general` expert now traverses the VocabBridge path (per-sample\n        # retokenise + char-offset align) instead of the same-tokenizer\n        # fast path. With CodeGPT-small-py still on the gpt2 vocab, the\n        # ensemble is 1 fast-path + 2 bridge-path experts after the\n        # swap. The per-position abstain logic from H21 is what makes\n        # this safe \u2014 every cross-tok expert correctly fills unmapped\n        # trunk slots at the uniform baseline.\n        experts: [\n            { id: \"smollm2_360m\",               domain: \"general\",   freeze: true },\n            { id: \"microsoft/CodeGPT-small-py\", domain: \"code\",      freeze: true },\n            { id: \"Qwen/Qwen2.5-0.5B\",          domain: \"reasoning\", freeze: true }\n        ],\n        trunk_tokenizer:     \"gpt2\",\n        freeze_weights:      true,\n        lexical_bias_weight: 2.0,\n        bema_tau:            0.5,\n        router_d_model:      256,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Slot A: KL-distillation aux loss \u2500\u2500\n        # The trunk learns FROM the cortex by matching its full output\n        # distribution, not just argmax targets. \u03bb_t is a piecewise-\n        # linear ramp in the EMA gap (lm_loss - cortex_loss); when the\n        # trunk has caught up (gap \u2264 floor) distillation goes idle.\n        # See docs/formal_framework.md \u00a79 (admission criterion) and\n        # tests/training/test_cortex_distillation_and_gating.py.\n        distillation_enabled:      true,\n        distillation_lambda_max:   1.0,\n        distillation_temperature:  4.0,\n        distillation_gap_floor:    0.1,\n        distillation_gap_ceiling:  2.0,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Slot C: NT-mediated \u03b1 gating \u2500\u2500\n        # \u03b1_eff = \u03b1 \u00b7 (1 - cortex_inhibition_level). The inhibition\n        # level rises smoothly as the trunk outperforms the cortex\n        # (acts like a GABA-inhibitory NT released by the trunk into\n        # the cortex region). Once saturated near 1 the cortex\n        # contributes ~nothing and inference can skip the cortex\n        # forward entirely (~20\u00d7 FLOP savings at the rcc_bowtie_30m_p4\n        # scale).\n        inhibition_enabled:        true,\n        inhibition_ema_alpha:      0.05,\n        inhibition_temperature:    1.0,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Item 2 (Jun 2026): NE \u2192 router temperature \u2500\u2500\n        # The locus coeruleus (NE) is the brain's gain channel. With\n        # this gain > 0 the harness pushes the live NE level into the\n        # router each step; logits are multiplied by\n        #   mult = clamp(1 + k_NE\u00b7z_NE, 0.1, 10.0)\n        # before softmax. mult > 1 sharpens routing (winner-take-most),\n        # mult < 1 softens it. k_NE = 0.5 gives a \u00b150% logit-scale\n        # swing across NE \u2208 [0, 1], plenty to register without ever\n        # collapsing the softmax to a one-hot.\n        router_temp_nt_gain:       0.5,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Item 3 (Jun 2026): 5HT/DA \u2192 distillation \u03bb \u2500\u2500\n        # The gap-ramp \u03bb is multiplied by\n        #   nt_mult = clamp(1 + k_5HT\u00b7z_5HT \u2212 k_DA\u00b7z_DA, 0, 2)\n        # so the trunk LEANS HARDER on the cortex when 5HT is high\n        # (stress / conservatism \u2014 trust the teacher) and LESS when\n        # DA is high (reward / explore \u2014 go your own way). Identical\n        # gains (0.4) keep the two channels balanced; an asymmetric\n        # split would prejudge the policy.\n        distillation_5ht_gain:     0.4,\n        distillation_da_gain:      0.4,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Item 4 (Jun 2026): GABA \u2192 lateral expert inhibition \u2500\u2500\n        # \u03ba_eff = \u03ba_base \u00b7 GABA. With \u03ba_base = 0.5 and GABA at its\n        # baseline (~0.15) the effective inhibition is ~0.075 \u2014 a\n        # gentle nudge toward specialisation that ramps as the\n        # homeostat raises GABA during high-ignition phases. The\n        # divisive normalisation is unconditionally on the simplex\n        # so the routing weights stay well-formed regardless of \u03ba.\n        lateral_inhibition_kappa:  0.5\n    }\n    # \u2500\u2500 Synthetic HPA axis \u2014 slow homeostatic stress damping \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n    # The existing neuromod stack has fast feedback (Homeostasis bumps\n    # GABA on grad spikes) but NO slow integrator. Result: NE can run\n    # away unchecked over ~40 steps (run 38470012: NE 0.20\u21920.93,\n    # gnorm 10\u219224, loss 12.6\u219215.4 between steps 460-500).\n    #\n    # `allostasis { ... }` adds the missing piece \u2014 a synthetic HPA\n    # axis with two state vars:\n    #   load(t) \u2014 fast EMA (\u03c4\u224810) of multi-modal stress (NE/GABA\n    #             excess, loss volatility, grad spikes), saturating.\n    #   cort(t) \u2014 slow EMA (\u03c4\u224834) of `load` \u2014 the cortisol integrator\n    #             that separates acute (single bad batch \u2014 leave alone)\n    #             from chronic (sustained \u2014 engage dampers).\n    #\n    # Three downstream multipliers, all in [0, 1] and applied each step:\n    #   ne_mult  = 1 - \u03b3_NE  \u00b7 cort  \u2192 caps NE release (closes the\n    #                                   LC positive-feedback loop)\n    #   troph_mult = 1 - \u03b3_T \u00b7 cort  \u2192 halts BDNF growth during crisis\n    #                                   (consolidate, don't sprout)\n    #   lr_mult  = 1 - \u03b3_LR \u00b7 cort   \u2192 damps optimizer LR (don't keep\n    #                                   updating chaotically)\n    #\n    # The 5\u00d7 HPA ratio (\u03b1_load=0.10, \u03b1_cort=0.02) makes brief spikes\n    # (1 bad batch + 99 calm) leave cort \u2248 0 \u2014 no damping for transient\n    # surprise \u2014 while sustained 200-step stress patterns drive cort\n    # past 0.25 where dampers begin to bite.\n    #\n    # See docs/findings.md H21 + tests/training/test_allostasis.py\n    # (38 contracts pinned including the smoking-gun replay of the\n    # actual 460\u2192500 runaway trajectory).\n    allostasis: {\n        enabled:           true,\n        load_ema_alpha:    0.10,\n        cort_ema_alpha:    0.02,\n        # Stress-source weights (sum to 1.0; the controller saturates\n        # the sum at 1 so this is bounded regardless).\n        w_ne:              0.30,\n        w_gaba:            0.20,\n        w_loss:            0.30,\n        w_grad:            0.20,\n        # Above-baseline thresholds (below these levels the channel\n        # contributes ZERO stress \u2014 tonic NT firing isn't pathological).\n        ne_baseline:       0.25,\n        gaba_baseline:     0.20,\n        grad_norm_ceiling: 5.0,\n        # All three effectors engaged. NE cap closes the runaway loop,\n        # trophic suppression stops growth during crisis, LR damping\n        # forces conservative updates instead of aggressive crisis-\n        # response weight changes (which is what diverged the run).\n        suppress_ne:       true,\n        suppress_trophic:  true,\n        suppress_lr:       true,\n        gamma_ne:          0.7,\n        gamma_trophic:     1.0,\n        gamma_lr:          0.5\n    }\n    # batch 16 x ctx 2048 = 32k tokens/step (same as old 32x1024) but\n    # ctx is 2x richer. The 32x2048 combo OOM'd on cross-entropy (13 GiB\n    # logit tensor at fp32). If you want to push back to batch=32, also\n    # port Brain's chunked CE (brain.py _chunked_ce) into the harness.\n    # ctx restored to 1024 + batch 32: throughput halved on ctx=2048\n    # (attention is O(seq^2)). Same 32k tok/step total, ~2x faster\n    # wall-clock. STACKED topology + dropout + pct carry the OOD wins;\n    # ctx-doubling was the lowest-impact regularizer in the original push.\n    # batch 16 x ctx 2048 = 32k tok/step (same total as prior 32x1024)\n    # but per-sequence context doubled. Long-range context matters for\n    # WikiText-103 OOD (academic prose has long-range deps). Throughput\n    # is 2x slower (attention O(seq^2)); proper fix would be to port\n    # Brain's chunked CE so we can run batch=32 ctx=2048 without OOM.\n    batch_size:   16\n    seq_len:      2048\n    steps:        40000\n    warmup_steps: 2400         # was 300 \u2014 scales with grad_accum=8 so we\n                                # still get 300 OPTIMIZER updates of warmup\n                                # (logged \"step\" counts micro-batches, not\n                                # opt updates). Prior 300 micro-batches =\n                                # 37 opt updates \u2192 too short, caused early\n                                # lurches at full LR.\n    min_lr_ratio: 0.1\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 C3 reentry as NT-gated trunk loss (Jun 2026) \u2500\u2500\n    # The PC reentry probe (predicting sensory hidden state from motor\n    # hidden state via a learned projection W) is no longer telemetry\n    # only \u2014 its residual is added to the LM loss, gradient flowing\n    # through BOTH populations so the trunk learns to make motor and\n    # sensory hidden states mutually predictive (a soft cycle-consistency\n    # / world-model constraint). Gating by neuromodulators:\n    #   gate = clip(1 + 0.5\u00b7DA \u2212 0.7\u00b7GABA, 0, \u221e)\n    # so the loss strengthens when DA is high (curiosity / reward) and\n    # weakens under GABA (cortical inhibition). eCB/5HT/Glu/etc. are\n    # left agnostic to avoid double-counting (they already modulate\n    # other parts of the homeostat).\n    pc_reentry_weight:  0.1\n    pc_reentry_nt_gate: true\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Item 6 (Jun 2026): trainable NT coupling matrix W \u2500\u2500\n    # When true, the DrivenNTSystem exposes its 7\u00d75 driver\u2192channel\n    # coupling matrix as an nn.Parameter (35 extra trainable scalars\n    # vs ~900M trunk + cortex params \u2014 negligible). The float OU\n    # dynamics in step_full() remain unchanged, so this flag never\n    # alters the numerical trajectory of `levels()` on its own.\n    # Gradient flows back to W_param only through differentiable\n    # downstream uses (router temperature, distillation \u03bb, lateral\n    # inhibition \u03ba) via predict_nt_tensor().\n    #\n    # SHIPPED DISABLED for the B5 sweep: Items 2/3/4 push float NT\n    # values into their consumers via plain dict `levels()`, which is\n    # all the optimisation signal we need to validate the GABA / NE /\n    # 5HT / DA mechanisms in isolation. Flipping this to `true` would\n    # add 35 trainable scalars whose gradient path is not yet wired\n    # to the consumers (would receive identically-zero grad \u2192 adds\n    # noise without learning signal). Re-enable once predict_nt_tensor\n    # is plumbed into the router / inhibition / distillation modules.\n    nt_w_trainable:     false\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Variational Bowtie Bottleneck (VBB) \u2014 Jun 2026 surgery \u2500\u2500\n    # The plain C3 PC-reentry residual was acting as a self-distillation\n    # amplifier: by step 4000 train ppl had halved (738\u2192426) while wiki\n    # ppl barely budged (3234\u21922899), pushing the gap ratio from 4.3 \u2192 6.8.\n    # VBB upgrades the residual into a Friston-style variational free\n    # energy at the bowtie waist:\n    #     L = \u03b3_NT \u00b7 ( \u03b2\u00b7\u2016s \u2212 W\u00b7(\u03bc + \u03c3\u00b7\u03b5)\u2016\u00b2 \u2212 log \u03b2 + \u03b1\u00b7KL[q \u2016 N(0,I)] )\n    # with q(h_m|x) = N(\u03bc, \u03c3\u00b2I), \u03bc = h_motor, log \u03c3\u00b2 = sigma_head(\u03bc).\n    # Three coupled mechanisms emerge:\n    #   1. KL[q \u2016 N(0,I)] is an Information Bottleneck at the narrowest\n    #      cross-section of the network \u2014 caps I(X; h_m), forbids\n    #      memorisation of training-distribution attractors.\n    #   2. \u03b2 = softplus(log_beta) self-throttles at \u03b2* = 1/(2\u00b7E[r]) via\n    #      the \u2212log \u03b2 log-normaliser. The loop stops being an amplifier\n    #      and becomes a calibrated generative model.\n    #   3. Reparam noise at the C3 read-site is structurally placed\n    #      stochastic gradient Langevin \u2014 biases SGD toward flat minima.\n    # Param overhead at d_sem=512: one Linear (262k) + one scalar = 0.21%.\n    # See harness._compute_pc_reentry_loss for the full math derivation.\n    vbb_alpha:     0.001\n    vbb_beta_init: 1.0\n    # \u2500\u2500 MDRV-VBB anti-collapse stabilisers (VBB-v2, Jun 2026) \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n    # Three interlocking mechanisms that prevent the \u03b2\u2191/\u03c3\u2193 co-collapse\n    # observed in the VBB-v1 run (gap 3.99\u21926.68 by step 4000):\n    #\n    #  1. Free-bits KL floor: guarantees \u22650.1 nats/dim of posterior\n    #     information \u2014 \u03c3\u21920 becomes provably non-optimal.\n    #  2. \u03b2-ceiling: clamps log \u03b2 \u2264 4.0 (\u03b2 \u2264 ~4.0) \u2014 breaks the\n    #     joint \u03b2\u2191/\u03c3\u2193 equilibrium that erased the bottleneck.\n    #  3. PEC (Posterior Entropy Commitment): Jeffreys prior on each\n    #     \u03c3_d \u2014 as \u03c3\u21920, PEC\u2192+\u221e, making collapse Lyapunov-unstable.\n    vbb_free_bits:    0.1\n    vbb_log_beta_max: 4.0\n    vbb_entropy_eta:  0.001\n    tonnetz_period: 0\n    bema_rollback_window: 0\n    bema_snapshot_every: 50\n    bema_cooldown: 100\n    nemori_floor: 0.0\n    mu_p_scaling: false\n    curriculum: \"random\"\n    crystallization_step: 0\n\n    # MAT-phase-gated mechanisms disabled for the 100M-genetics run.\n    # The MAT-ramp regularization was crippling early LM convergence\n    # (134M with phase-gated dropout active was 100+ ppl behind the 30M\n    # baseline at step 2500). Targets: loss<4, ppl<100 by step 10k \u2014\n    # pure-baseline trunk is closest to the 30M-on-30M run that hit\n    # them. Genetics still active but selected for LM-loss (below).\n    mechanisms: {}\n\n    # Declarative early-exit conditions. First rule to fire saves a\n    # checkpoint and exits the training loop. NOTE: only the \"OOD keeps\n    # falling\" rule is active \u2014 the step-thresholded fail-fast rules were\n    # removed (they were triggering on early-training noise).\n    #\n    # Rule: exit when OOD-ppl trend stalls. Compares min(OOD) in the first\n    # half of the window vs min(OOD) in the second half. Requires\n    # `min_evals` data points before it can fire, so transient single-eval\n    # noise (~3% on a 50-window WikiText eval) can't trigger exit on its\n    # own. `tol: 0.02` = require a real \u22652% improvement.\n    pass_marks: {\n        # Hard target: ppl < 100 at step 10k.\n        ppl_at_10k:   { metric: \"train_ppl\", at_step: 10000, max: 100 }\n        # OOD trend rule (loose \u2014 5 evals, 2% tol) as the success-exit.\n        ood_not_falling: {\n            metric: \"ood_ppl\",\n            window: 4000,\n            trend: \"falling\",\n            tol: 0.02,\n            min_evals: 5\n        }\n    }\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a76.5 Genetics \u2500\u2500\n    # optimize_for: \"lm_loss\" \u2014 genes train ONLY through the cortex's\n    # alpha_nt \u2192 LM gradient path. No -Phi aux term (phi_weight forced\n    # to 0). This avoids the prior failure mode where genes were pulled\n    # toward Phi-good but LM-bad configurations during early training,\n    # hurting the LM convergence rate.\n    # ReZero payload + alpha_nt=0 init means the cortex is bit-identical\n    # to baseline at step 0; the gate only opens if doing so reduces LM.\n    genetics: {\n        enabled:            true\n        n_genes:            32\n        d_pay:              16\n        optimize_for:       \"lm_loss\"\n        fixed_genes_preset: \"default\"\n        update_every:       4\n        diagnostics_every:  50\n    }\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Hardware envelope \u2500\u2500\n    # Deploy script filters vast.ai offers by these constraints.\n    # `dist_strategy`: \"single\" | \"ddp\" | \"fsdp\". Picked per scale below\n    # (large scales auto-override). Precision = bf16 (A100/H100 native).\n    # min_gpu_mem_gib: A100 SXM4 ships in 40 GB and 80 GB variants;\n    # without this filter vast.ai sometimes serves up tiny 16/20 GB\n    # MIG-sliced A100s ($0.7/hr range) that OOM at the first forward.\n    hardware: {\n        gpu_name:        \"A100_SXM4\"\n        num_gpus:        1\n        min_gpu_mem_gib: 40\n        min_reliability: 0.995\n        min_inet_mbps:   200\n        dist_strategy:   \"single\"\n        precision:       \"bf16\"\n    }\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Multi-scale variants of the same architecture \u2500\u2500\n    # Pick at deploy time via env SCALE=<name>. Each variant inherits\n    # the global `hardware` block unless it declares its own override.\n    # approx_params is informational (rough trunk-only count).\n    scales: {\n        default: \"30m_p4\"\n\n        30m_p4: {\n            d_model:       512\n            depth:         8\n            n_heads:       8\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    1       # T4 GPU memory: 16 GiB fits 1\u00d7512 ctx comfortably\n            seq_len:       512     # reduces attn memory (O(T\u00b2) per head); was 2048\n            grad_accum:    4       # compensates for batch=1; maintains training signal\n            approx_params: \"30M\"\n        }\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Cheap-hardware 2k smoke run \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n        # Target: short (~2 hour) end-to-end smoke run on a $0.15-0.30/hr\n        # vast.ai instance \u2014 RTX 3090 / RTX 4090 / A5000 / RTX 4000 Ada.\n        # Used to verify that a DSL/DNA change boots cleanly + the MoE\n        # experts ensemble produces real loss before paying for full A100\n        # runs. NOT a research run; trajectories \u22642k steps are noise.\n        # Per CLAUDE.md \u00a710, even smoke runs are recorded as findings.\n        cheap_2k: {\n            d_model:       512\n            depth:         8\n            n_heads:       8\n            max_ctx:       1024   # 2\u00d7 the 30m_p4 ctx; still fits ~10 GiB\n            batch_size:    2      # double the signal/step of 30m_p4\n            seq_len:       1024\n            grad_accum:    2      # 4k tok/step \u2014 enough to dampen jitter\n            approx_params: \"30M\"\n            hardware: {\n                # RTX 3090 is the sweet spot: 24 GiB headroom for the\n                # 3 frozen MoE experts (~1.5 GiB fp16 each w/ activations),\n                # widely available at $0.15-0.25/hr; ~5x cheaper than A100.\n                gpu_name:        \"RTX_3090\"\n                num_gpus:        1\n                min_gpu_mem_gib: 20\n                min_reliability: 0.98\n                min_inet_mbps:   100\n                dist_strategy:   \"single\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n\n        100m: {\n            # Honest ~100M: trunk + embedding + lm_head \u2248 103M.\n            # (The previous 768/10 config was 204M because embedding +\n            #  lm_head + diff-block doublings added ~94M on top.)\n            # Layout: depth=8 with i%3 pattern \u2192 3 std + 3 diff + 2 mod\n            # blocks. 3 diff-attention blocks each need 2 \u00d7 (B, H, T, T)\n            # softmax tensors \u2014 at B=4 H=10 T=2048 bf16 that's ~1.6 GiB\n            # per block, ~5 GiB total. Comfortable on a 40 GiB A100.\n            d_model:       640\n            depth:         8\n            n_heads:       10\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    4\n            seq_len:       2048\n            grad_accum:    4\n            approx_params: \"~100M\"\n        }\n\n        300m: {\n            d_model:       1024\n            depth:         24\n            n_heads:       16\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    8\n            seq_len:       2048\n            grad_accum:    2\n            approx_params: \"300M\"\n            hardware: {\n                gpu_name:        \"A100_SXM4\"\n                num_gpus:        2\n                min_reliability: 0.995\n                min_inet_mbps:   200\n                dist_strategy:   \"ddp\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n\n        1b: {\n            d_model:       2048\n            depth:         24\n            n_heads:       16\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    4\n            seq_len:       2048\n            grad_accum:    4\n            approx_params: \"1B\"\n            hardware: {\n                gpu_name:        \"A100_SXM4\"\n                num_gpus:        4\n                min_reliability: 0.995\n                min_inet_mbps:   200\n                dist_strategy:   \"ddp\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n\n        7b: {\n            d_model:       4096\n            depth:         32\n            n_heads:       32\n            max_ctx:       4096\n            batch_size:    2\n            seq_len:       4096\n            grad_accum:    8\n            approx_params: \"7B\"\n            hardware: {\n                gpu_name:        \"H100_SXM\"\n                num_gpus:        8\n                min_reliability: 0.995\n                min_inet_mbps:   500\n                dist_strategy:   \"fsdp\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    # =========================================================================\n    # OOD INTERVENTIONS (regularization {})  \u2014 see docs/technical_report.md \u00a73\n    # Math-first definitions live in lib/regularizers.neuro.\n    #\n    # 2026-06-03 GROUND-TRUTH BASELINE\n    # \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n    # ALL interventions disabled. Four iterations of \"fixes\" (warmup ramp \u2192\n    # PR-A1 direction flip \u2192 neuromechanical stabilisation) each closed one\n    # failure mode and opened another. We never measured what vanilla\n    # training looks like at this scale, so we have no baseline to fix\n    # against. This run establishes that baseline.\n    #\n    # Re-enable individual interventions ONLY after we know what\n    # `wikitext gap_ratio` looks like with no interventions at chat_ratio\u22480.3.\n    # =========================================================================\n    regularization: {\n        # \u2500\u2500 WARMUP RAMP \u2014 REMOVED 2026-06-03 \u2500\u2500\n        # warmup_steps controlled a linear 0\u21921 ramp on all aux loss\n        # contributions. With every intervention disabled in this\n        # baseline config there is nothing to ramp, so the field has\n        # been removed to make the no-op explicit. When re-enabling\n        # any of (dar, pcc, isotropy, cmd, adaptive_mixture, cdga)\n        # restore `warmup_steps: 2000` here.\n\n        # A. Distributional Adversarial Reweighting \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        dar: { enabled: false, lambda: 1.0, hidden: 64, grl_alpha: 0.1,\n               weight: 0.1 }\n\n        # B. Predictive Contrastive Coding \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        pcc: { enabled: false, k: 4, n_negatives: 64, tau: 0.1, layers: [],\n               weight: 0.1 }\n\n        # C. Isotropy whitening \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        isotropy: { enabled: false, weight: 0.01, buffer: 4096, distance: \"frobenius\" }\n\n        # D. Cross-Module Disagreement \u2014 DISABLED (OOM at this batch+seq).\n        cmd: { enabled: false, weight: 0.05, divergence: \"jsd\",\n               heads: [\"lm\", \"narrative\"] }\n\n        # E. Adaptive mixture controller \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        #    (The controller is architecturally blind to prose: it sees\n        #    entropy of the MIXED training batch, dominated by chat. It\n        #    cannot detect the prose-ppl collapse we observed at step\n        #    1000 of the previous run. Will be redesigned with a true\n        #    held-out probe before re-enabling.)\n        adaptive_mixture: { enabled: false, target_entropy: 4.5,\n                            probe_interval: 100, gamma: 2.0,\n                            direction: \"balance\",\n                            min_ratio: 0.10, max_ratio: 0.50,\n                            controller_warmup_steps: 2000,\n                            max_step_delta: 0.03,\n                            entropy_ema_alpha: 0.1 }\n\n        # F. Frequency-balanced cross-entropy \u2014 DISABLED (needs corpus scan).\n        freq_balance: { enabled: false, beta: 0.5,\n                        w_min: 0.2, w_max: 5.0 }\n\n        # G. Cross-Distribution Gradient Alignment (CDGA) \u2014 DISABLED\n        #    (research-grade, kept off until ground-truth baseline is\n        #    established and an anchor batch loader is wired in).\n        cdga: { enabled: false, alpha_max: 1.0,\n                warmup_steps: 2000, refresh_every: 4 }\n    }\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# PARAMETER SCOPES \u2014 declarative gradient isolation (the p3 architectural\n# fix). Bio-side populations are detached from the main LM loss; they're\n# driven by their own auxiliary objectives (Phase D), not by token CE.\n# The trunk carries the language-modeling gradient.\n# =============================================================================\n\nparam_scope trunk {\n    populations: [sensory, association, thalamus, world, self_m, qualia, gws, neural_geometry, entorhinal, pfc, acc, forward_m, evaluator, dmn, thought_transformer, claustrum, motor, reasoning_cortex, cortex_math, cortex_code, cortex_chat, cortex_general]\n}\n\nparam_scope bio {\n    populations: [amygdala, insula, hippo, cerebellum, bg, vta, nucleus_accumbens, locus_coeruleus, raphe_nuclei, nucleus_basalis, substantia_nigra],\n    gradient: \"detached_from_main_loss\"\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# NEUROTRANSMITTER SYSTEMS (7 classical) \u2014 globally visible\n# =============================================================================\n\nneurotransmitter dopamine {\n    base_concentration: 0.10,\n    release_rate: 0.20,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.80,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.02\n}\n\nneurotransmitter norepinephrine {\n    base_concentration: 0.15,\n    release_rate: 0.30,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.70,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.015\n}\n\nneurotransmitter serotonin {\n    base_concentration: 0.30,\n    release_rate: 0.05,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.95,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.01\n}\n\nneurotransmitter acetylcholine {\n    base_concentration: 0.20,\n    release_rate: 0.25,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.75,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.025\n}\n\nneurotransmitter endocannabinoid {\n    base_concentration: 0.05,\n    release_rate: 0.40,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.60,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.03\n}\n\nneurotransmitter glutamate {\n    base_concentration: 0.40,\n    release_rate: 0.50,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.50,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.02\n}\n\nneurotransmitter gaba {\n    base_concentration: 0.10,\n    release_rate: 0.10,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.90,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.01\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# LIBRARY IMPORTS \u2014 shared equations, constraints, regularization\n# =============================================================================\n\n# Canonical shared lib. The 3 standard equations live in @brian/equations\n# alongside the 5 feature-toggleable equations (hyperbolic_attention_eq,\n# rope_torus_eq, hrr_memory_eq, predictive_coding_residual_eq,\n# surprise_gated_moe_eq) \u2014 importing the whole shared registry from one\n# place avoids the local-shadow conflict that arose when both\n# `@/lib/equations` and `@brian/equations` resolved to the same bundled\n# `lib/equations.neuro` at unfold time and the local 3-symbol shadow\n# silently overwrote the canonical 8-symbol source of truth.\nimport { standard_synapse, multiplicative_modulation, additive_modulation } from \"@brian/equations\"\n# Regularizer & CDGA equation libraries \u2014 math-first declarative specs\n# for the OOD interventions (PR2 + PR-A + PR-B). The Python lowerings\n# live in neuroslm/regularizers.py and read their hyperparameters from\n# the `regularization { ... }` block above.\nimport { adaptive_mixture_update, freq_balance_loss, freq_balance_weight } from \"@/lib/regularizers\"\nimport { cdga_conflict_coef, cdga_aligned_gradient, cdga_strength_schedule } from \"@/lib/cdga\"\n\n# Emergent-topology library \u2014 math-first declarations for the six\n# closed-loop telemetry mechanisms (C1\u2013C6) introduced in RCC-Bowtie v2.\n# See docs/EMERGENT_TOPOLOGY.md for the design rationale. The Python\n# lowering lives in neuroslm/emergent/ and is wired into the metric\n# observer by default. Telemetry-only in this PR; promotion of any\n# mechanism into a forward-pass aux loss is a future PR.\nimport { nt_driver_standardise, nt_homeostat_step, nt_homeostat_readout } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { metastable_ignition_gate, metastable_ignition_event, metastable_threshold_update } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { pc_reentry_predict, pc_reentry_residual } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { topological_unit_field, topological_complex_pair, topological_phase_increment, topological_charge_total, topological_wall_indicator } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { lattice_slice_winner, lattice_specialisation_index } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { pac_bandpass_analytic, pac_phase_and_amplitude, pac_modulation_index } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\n\n# =============================================================================\n# TOGGLEABLE MECHANISMS (\u00a714 \u2014 declared inactive; activation = ablation)\n# =============================================================================\n# Five toggleable mechanisms from the shared @brian library. Each pairs\n# a real PyTorch impl (under neuroslm/modules/) with TDD-pinned math\n# contracts (under tests/). The feature blocks below import the\n# canonical equations + impl bindings; `active: false` keeps each one\n# bypassed at runtime so this baseline arch is byte-identical to the\n# pre-mechanism build. To run an ablation, copy-paste a feature block\n# below and flip `active: true` (and optionally tune its `params:`).\n#\n# See docs/features/<name>.md for hypothesis + math + wiring example.\nimport { hyperbolic_attention }          from \"@brian/features/hyperbolic_attention\"\nimport { rope_torus }                    from \"@brian/features/rope_torus\"\nimport { hrr_memory }                    from \"@brian/features/hrr_memory\"\nimport { predictive_coding_residual }    from \"@brian/features/predictive_coding_residual\"\nimport { surprise_gated_moe }            from \"@brian/features/surprise_gated_moe\"\n\n# =============================================================================\n# \u00a714 FEATURE ACTIVATION \u2014 flip mechanisms ON for this architecture\n# =============================================================================\n# Per CLAUDE.md \u00a714 the shared lib defines every feature with\n# `active: false` (clean baseline). The arch-local re-declarations\n# below override only the `active` flag \u2014 impl/params/endpoints are\n# inherited from the lib spec via the compiler's merge-by-name pass.\n# To run an ablation just delete (or comment out) the matching block\n# to revert that mechanism to its bypassed baseline.\n\nfeature hyperbolic_attention {\n    equation: hyperbolic_attention_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature rope_torus {\n    equation: rope_torus_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature hrr_memory {\n    equation: hrr_memory_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature predictive_coding_residual {\n    equation: predictive_coding_residual_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature surprise_gated_moe {\n    equation: surprise_gated_moe_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# MODULE IMPORTS \u2014 every brain region this architecture comprises\n# =============================================================================\n\nimport { sensory, association }                          from \"@/modules/sensory\"\nimport { thalamus }                                       from \"@/modules/thalamus\"\nimport { world, self_m }                                  from \"@/modules/world\"\nimport { amygdala, insula }                               from \"@/modules/amygdala\"\nimport { qualia }                                         from \"@/modules/qualia\"\nimport { gws, neural_geometry }                           from \"@/modules/gws\"\nimport { hippo, entorhinal, cerebellum }                  from \"@/modules/hippocampus\"\nimport { pfc, acc }                                       from \"@/modules/pfc\"\nimport { bg, forward_m, evaluator }                       from \"@/modules/bg\"\nimport { dmn, thought_transformer, claustrum }            from \"@/modules/dmn\"\nimport { motor }                                          from \"@/modules/motor\"\nimport { vta, nucleus_accumbens, locus_coeruleus, raphe_nuclei, nucleus_basalis, substantia_nigra } from \"@/modules/nuclei\"\nimport { reasoning_cortex }                               from \"@/modules/reasoning_cortex\"\n# Multi-Trunk-v2 specialist language cortices \u2014 see Section 5.7 of\n# docs/architecture.md.  The dynamic per-token routing lives in\n# neuroslm/cortex.py (ThalamicRouter); the DSL declarations below\n# expose the four cortices to the analyser, the param_scope, and the\n# bowtie's synaptic wiring.\nimport { cortex_math, cortex_code, cortex_chat, cortex_general } from \"@/modules/cortex_specialists\"\n\n# =============================================================================\n# ANATOMICAL PROJECTIONS (cross-module synaptic wiring)\n# Equation: y = weight * (x_pre @ W) \u2014 PyTorch-batched linear projection.\n# =============================================================================\n\n# Thalamic gating (sensory bottleneck control)\nsynapse thalamus -> gws {\n    weight: 0.8, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Multi-Trunk-v2 thalamic routing (see \u00a75.7 of docs/architecture.md) \u2500\u2500\n# Four parallel projections from the thalamus to the specialist\n# language cortices.  Static `weight: 0.25` declares a uniform \u0394^4 prior\n# at the DSL level; the per-token, content-dependent weights are\n# computed at run-time by `neuroslm.cortex.ThalamicRouter` (lexical\n# bias + zero-init learnable head + optional BEMA biological damping)\n# and override these static priors during the forward pass.\n#\n# Mathematical contract (cf. Sherman & Guillery 2002, Halassa & Kastner\n# 2017): the thalamus is the brain's central gating bus; one synapse\n# per cortical specialist makes the gradient routing explicit, and\n# `param_scope trunk` keeps all four cortices on the language gradient.\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_math {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_code {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_chat {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_general {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# State models \u2192 workspace\nsynapse world -> gws {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #4: predictive-coding residual \u2500\u2500\n    # World-model \u2192 conscious-workspace edge is the canonical sensory\n    # surface in PC (Rao-Ballard 1999). The trunk prediction g(x) is\n    # subtracted out; only the surprise (x - g(x)), scaled by alpha=0.1,\n    # propagates forward. See docs/features/predictive_coding_residual.md.\n    feature: \"predictive_coding_residual.edge\"\n}\nsynapse self_m -> gws {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# GWS \u2192 memory (every conscious access broadcasts to hippocampus)\nsynapse gws -> hippo {\n    weight: 0.7, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# GWS \u2192 cognitive control (top-down planning)\nsynapse gws -> pfc {\n    weight: 0.8, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #1: hyperbolic attention \u2500\u2500\n    # The semantic broadcast from the conscious workspace to executive\n    # control carries tree-shaped context (task hierarchy, plan\n    # subgoals); a Poincar\u00e9-disc metric (volume \u221d e^r) is the natural\n    # geometry. Ganea/B\u00e9cigneul/Hofmann 2018.\n    feature: \"hyperbolic_attention.edge\"\n}\nsynapse gws -> acc {\n    weight: 0.7, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# PFC \u2192 basal ganglia (action selection)\nsynapse pfc -> bg {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #5: surprise-gated MoE \u2500\u2500\n    # Action-selection cost should scale with how uncertain the policy\n    # is. SurpriseGatedMoE routes confident tokens to k_min=1 expert\n    # (cheap) and uncertain tokens to k_max=4 (rich mixture). Free-\n    # energy principle (Friston 2010) made concrete in compute budget.\n    feature: \"surprise_gated_moe.edge\"\n}\n\n# Basal ganglia \u2192 motor (action execution; GABAergic disinhibition)\nsynapse bg -> motor {\n    weight: 0.8, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Forward model + evaluator feedback\nsynapse forward_m -> evaluator {\n    weight: 0.7, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Memory feedback \u2192 PFC (recall-guided planning)\nsynapse hippo -> pfc {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #3: HRR-bound holographic memory \u2500\u2500\n    # The hippocampus-to-PFC recall edge is exactly the content-\n    # addressable retrieval HRR was invented for (Plate 1995). Per-batch\n    # memory M = \u03a3_t bind(k_t, v_t); per-token query unbinds the\n    # superposition.\n    feature: \"hrr_memory.edge\"\n}\nsynapse entorhinal -> pfc {\n    weight: 0.4, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Re-entry loop: PFC back to thalamus (bowtie closure \u2192 \u03a6 > 0)\nsynapse pfc -> thalamus {\n    weight: 0.3, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #2: RoPE-on-Torus \u2500\u2500\n    # The bowtie closure carries iteration position around the re-entry\n    # loop \u2014 naturally cyclic, naturally multi-scale (token, episode,\n    # session). Per-slice torus periods (Su et al. 2024, generalised)\n    # encode this directly into the transmission.\n    feature: \"rope_torus.edge\"\n}\n\n# DMN \u2192 GWS (narrative broadcasts to conscious access)\nsynapse dmn -> gws {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Cerebellum \u2192 forward model (classical conditioning, motor learning)\nsynapse cerebellum -> forward_m {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# STACKED OOD TOPOLOGY (added after run 38569395 OOD gap_ratio 7.04)\n# Three independent mechanisms layered together. Surfaced by\n# `brian analyze rcc_bowtie --topo-10x`. Generalization proxy +63.5%.\n#\n#   1. PCT-style reentry: motor errors feed back to sensory.\n#      (matches B3 / PCT-30M from the OOD ablation arc which hit 4.51)\n#   2. MoE parallel path through reasoning_cortex (cuts OOD interference\n#      via specialised routing; lottery-ticket / sparse-routing lit).\n#   3. Lateral inhibition (GABA) between dmn and reasoning_cortex\n#      (sparse-coding effect: one specialised lane fires per token).\n# =============================================================================\n\n# (1) Reentry: deep motor -> sensory loop (closes the bowtie)\nsynapse motor -> sensory {\n    weight: 0.4, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# (2) MoE parallel path: pfc -> reasoning_cortex -> motor\nsynapse pfc -> reasoning_cortex {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse reasoning_cortex -> motor {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# (3) Lateral inhibition: dmn <-> reasoning_cortex (GABA)\nsynapse dmn -> reasoning_cortex {\n    weight: 0.3, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse reasoning_cortex -> dmn {\n    weight: 0.3, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# NEUROMODULATION (receptor banks \u2014 fast NT modulation of regions)\n# Equation: y = output * (c * gain)        for multiplicative effects\n# Equation: y = output + (c * gain)        for additive effects\n# c = NT concentration in nt_levels dict   gain = receptor sensitivity\n# =============================================================================\n\n# PFC \u2014 DA (motivation), 5HT (impulse control), ACh (attention), GABA (inhibition)\nmodulation dopamine -> pfc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.6,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation serotonin -> pfc {\n    effect: \"additive\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @additive_modulation\n}\nmodulation acetylcholine -> pfc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.4,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation gaba -> pfc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.4,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# Hippocampus \u2014 ACh (encoding), Glu (binding)\nmodulation acetylcholine -> hippo {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation glutamate -> hippo {\n    effect: \"additive\", gain: 0.4,\n    equation: @additive_modulation\n}\n\n# Basal ganglia \u2014 DA (motivation), GABA (competition)\nmodulation dopamine -> bg {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.7,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation gaba -> bg {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# Thalamus \u2014 NE (arousal), GABA (relay control)\nmodulation norepinephrine -> thalamus {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation gaba -> thalamus {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# Sensory \u2014 ACh (attention), eCB (inhibition)\nmodulation acetylcholine -> sensory {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation endocannabinoid -> sensory {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# DMN \u2014 5HT (introspection dampening), ACh (attention)\nmodulation serotonin -> dmn {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.6,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation acetylcholine -> dmn {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.2,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# GWS \u2014 DA (salience boost)\nmodulation dopamine -> gws {\n    effect: \"additive\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @additive_modulation\n}\n\n# Amygdala \u2014 5HT (fear suppression via raphe)\nmodulation serotonin -> amygdala {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.7,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# ACC \u2014 DA (motivation)\nmodulation dopamine -> acc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# FORMAL CONSTRAINT SYSTEMS \u2014 imported from lib/constraints.neuro\n# =============================================================================\n# Three core constraints that govern topology and ensure biological realism:\n#   1. Narrative Consistency (sheaf cohomology proxy for narrative coherence)\n#   2. Integrated Information (\u03a6 > 0 per Tononi 4.0 formalism)\n#   3. Bowtie Topology (narrowing-widening structure with re-entry)\n#\n# Math-first definitions live in lib/constraints.neuro. The linter verifies\n# these at compile time; the harness applies them as auxiliary losses at runtime.\n# =============================================================================\n\n# =============================================================================\n# THSD (Topological Hyper-Sheaf Dynamics) \u2014 Brain Regions as Simplicial Complexes\n# =============================================================================\n# Each brain region is formalized as a simplicial complex \u03c3\u1d48\u1d62 with:\n#   - SheafStalk: local representation space with Fisher information metric\n#   - Topology: Tonnetz manifold with spectral gap \u03bb\u2081 > 0.3\n#   - FormalSpec: cohomological constraints H\u00b9(K;F), \u03a6 maximization\n#   - Dynamics: vesicle-based mutations, NEMORI consolidation\n\n# Sensory input layer \u2014 thalamic gateway to conscious access\ncomplex Thalamus {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 256,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"predictive_consistency\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.32,\n        dimension: 6,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.95\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.005,\n        phi_target: 0.80,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\",\n        information_bottleneck: {\n            enabled: true,\n            compression_ratio: 0.7,\n            prediction_lower_bound: 0.92\n        }\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        emission {\n            trigger: \"surprise_head(threshold=0.8)\",\n            payload_dim: 64,\n            lifetime_steps: 100\n        },\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 1000,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.01\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# Global workspace (conscious space) \u2014 recurrent amplification & integration\ncomplex GlobalWorkspace {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 512,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"narrative_consistency\", \"gradient_stability\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.35,\n        dimension: 8,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.98\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.008,\n        phi_target: 0.85,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\",\n        information_bottleneck: {\n            enabled: true,\n            compression_ratio: 0.65,\n            prediction_lower_bound: 0.94\n        }\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        emission {\n            trigger: \"always\",\n            payload_dim: 96,\n            lifetime_steps: 150\n        },\n        release {\n            rule: \"rank_one_update\",\n            learning_rate: 0.001,\n            target: \"parameter_counts\"\n        },\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 800,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.005\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# Prefrontal cortex (executive control) \u2014 planning & decision-making\ncomplex PrefrontalCortex {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 384,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"planning_consistency\", \"value_alignment\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.33,\n        dimension: 7,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.96\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.006,\n        phi_target: 0.82,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\",\n        information_bottleneck: {\n            enabled: true,\n            compression_ratio: 0.72,\n            prediction_lower_bound: 0.93\n        }\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        emission {\n            trigger: \"surprise_head(threshold=0.7)\",\n            payload_dim: 80,\n            lifetime_steps: 120\n        },\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 900,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.008\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# Motor output layer \u2014 action generation\ncomplex MotorCortex {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 192,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"motor_smoothness\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.30,\n        dimension: 5,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.94\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.004,\n        phi_target: 0.75,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\"\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 1200,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.012\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# TRIPLE GUARD \u2014 live admission gate for auto-evolution\n# =============================================================================\n# Normative reference: docs/formal_framework.md \u00a77.\n#\n# Every mutation proposed during training (rank-one DNA patches, structural\n# rewires, gene drifts) is gated by the (\u03a6 \u2227 H\u00b9 \u2227 \u03bb\u2081) admission criteria\n# below.  Mutations that *would* drive any of the three scores out-of-band\n# are dropped before they reach disk; rejected mutations are persisted to\n# a sibling `step_<N>.rejected.json` audit file so the human + the\n# evolutionary loop can both see what the architecture refused to become.\n#\n# The thresholds below are intentionally PERMISSIVE for pretraining (see\n# the \"PRETRAIN-FRIENDLY RECIPE\" note further up \u2014 early infancy must be\n# allowed to wander).  They are the *safety net*, not yet the *fitness\n# pressure*; tighten them after the trunk reaches its capacity ceiling.\n#\n#   phi_min     \u2014 minimum admissible \u03a6 after mutation; 0.0 disables.\n#   h1_max      \u2014 maximum admissible \u2016H\u00b9(K;F)\u2016 proxy; matches the default\n#                 hallucination_threshold in CohomologyValidator (5.0).\n#   lambda_min  \u2014 minimum admissible spectral-gap proxy \u03bb\u2081; 0.0 disables\n#                 until the \u00a74.2 Tonnetz Resonance Filter lands as a real\n#                 Laplacian computation.\n#\n# Code path: TripleGuard.from_arch_neuro(arch_path) reads this block;\n# EvolutionaryTrainingContext.set_triple_guard(guard) installs it; the\n# harness's mutation step then calls ctx.save_checkpoint(step, muts, pairs)\n# which routes through the guard.  See tests/training/test_rcc_bowtie_triple_guard.py\n# for the full contract.\nexport formal_spec triple_guard_admission {\n    rule: \"triple_guard\",\n    phi_min: 0.0,\n    h1_max: 5.0,\n    lambda_min: 0.0\n}\n\nimport { sheaf_narrative_consistency, formal_phi_integration, formal_bowtie_topology } from \"@/lib/constraints\"\n",
  "bundled_dsl": {
   "main_source": "    # -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# RCC Bowtie \u2014 package config + global wiring\n#\n# This `arch.neuro` is the architecture's entry point. It sets runtime\n# defaults, declares the 7 classical neurotransmitter systems globally,\n# pulls in every brain-region module via `import`, then defines the\n# cross-module synaptic wiring + neuromodulator routing.\n#\n# Per-region module files live under modules/; they declare populations\n# and (optionally) their local internal wiring. Shared mechanics live\n# under lib/.\n#\n# Topology: bowtie with re-entry (sensory \u2192 thalamus \u2192 GWS \u2192 PFC \u2192 ...\n# \u2192 thalamus). IIT 4.0 compliant (every part has both causes and effects\n# in the system \u2192 \u03a6 > 0).\n#\n# References \u2014 Dehaene (2011), Baars (2005), Doya (1999), Tononi (2016),\n# Mashour (2020).\n\n# Equations are imported from lib/equations.neuro (see MODULE IMPORTS below).\n# This keeps arch.neuro free of implementation details and focuses it on\n# high-level architecture + wiring + constraints.\n\narchitecture rcc_bowtie {\n    d_sem: 256,\n    dt: 0.01\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# TRAINING \u2014 pipeline behavior the BRIAN harness applies on top of the\n# compiled DSL circuit. Loss clipping here is the declarative form of the\n# p4 architectural fix (was: cfg.loss_clip_robust=True, factor=3.0).\n# =============================================================================\n\ntraining {\n    # MAT-phase-gated mechanisms + declarative early-exit pass marks.\n    # `preset` sets the trunk dims (overrides env PRESET when set).\n    # See docs/OOD_PUSH_STAGES.md + docs/metrics.md.\n    preset:        \"rcc_bowtie_30m_p4\"\n    loss_clipping: { enabled: true, method: \"per_sample\", factor: 3.0 }\n    quantization:  { enabled: false, bits: 8 }\n    optimizer:     \"adamw\"\n    learning_rate: 0.0005      # was 3e-4 \u2014 pushed up after fair-fight run\n                                # showed lots of headroom (gnorm stable at\n                                # 1-2, no instability); 5e-4 is GPT-2-medium-class\n    # \u2554\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2557\n    # \u2551  PRETRAIN-FRIENDLY RECIPE  (Jun 2026 surgery)                \u2551\n    # \u2551                                                              \u2551\n    # \u2551  The previous values (wd=0.12 dropout=0.12 llrd=0.85         \u2551\n    # \u2551  flooding=4.0 label_smooth=0.05) were tuned to NARROW the    \u2551\n    # \u2551  train\u2192WikiText OOD gap after ~10k steps of an already-      \u2551\n    # \u2551  pretrained checkpoint. Applied from-scratch they suppress   \u2551\n    # \u2551  early learning catastrophically:                            \u2551\n    # \u2551    \u2022 flooding=4.0 hard-caps train ppl at \u224855 \u2014 model is      \u2551\n    # \u2551      contractually forbidden from improving below ln(55)\u22484   \u2551\n    # \u2551    \u2022 LLRD=0.85 over 8 depth + adapters (~170 groups) starves \u2551\n    # \u2551      bottom layers at 0.85^20 \u2248 4% of base LR                \u2551\n    # \u2551    \u2022 dropout=0.12 + wd=0.12 are anti-regularisers when the   \u2551\n    # \u2551      model is severely under-fit (train ppl 500+)            \u2551\n    # \u2551                                                              \u2551\n    # \u2551  New values are GPT-2 / LLaMA pretraining defaults. Once the \u2551\n    # \u2551  trunk reaches its capacity ceiling (train ppl < ~30), the   \u2551\n    # \u2551  OOD-narrowing knobs can be re-enabled via the PR2           \u2551\n    # \u2551  regularization controller (DAR/PCC/iso/CMD) which is        \u2551\n    # \u2551  designed to compose additively without poisoning early      \u2551\n    # \u2551  training. See docs/PRETRAIN_RECIPE.md.                      \u2551\n    # \u255a\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u255d\n    weight_decay:  0.01        # was 0.12 \u2014 GPT-2/LLaMA use 0.01\u20130.1\n    grad_accum:    8           # was 1 \u2014 batch=4 \u00d7 ctx=2048 \u00d7 accum=8 = 65k\n                                # tok/step (~12% of GPT-2's 524k). Prior\n                                # 8k tok/step caused \u00b135% loss swings from\n                                # micro-batch noise; this kills the jitter\n                                # at zero VRAM cost (one extra fwd+bwd, no\n                                # extra activations stored).\n    grad_clip:     1.0\n    label_smoothing: 0.0       # was 0.05 \u2014 inflates raw PPL, off for pretrain\n    dropout:       0.0         # was 0.12 \u2014 model is under-fit, no overfit yet\n    flooding_level: 0.0        # was 4.0 \u2014 DEATH SENTENCE for pretraining\n    stochastic_depth: 0.0      # was 0.1  \u2014 reduces effective depth\n    z_loss: 0.0001             # keep \u2014 cheap PaLM-style logit stabiliser\n    llrd: 1.0                  # was 0.85 \u2014 LLRD is for FINE-TUNING, not pretrain\n    pct_trunk:     0.0\n    pct_strength:  0.0\n    # \u2500\u2500 HPB Phases 1-5 \u2014 novel-topology mechanisms ACTIVATED \u2500\u2500\n    # All zero-init: first forward is bit-identical to baseline; behaviour\n    # emerges as the gates lift off zero under LM loss. Composable \u2014\n    # H19 monitors surprise (read by H15 for analytics when write_gate\n    # is \"surprise\"; currently \"all\" for the Phase-5 uniform-writes\n    # baseline before the wake/sleep replay loop (Phase 6) lands.\n    #\n    # HPB Phase 1 + Phase 2: H16 multi-scale grid-cell positions.\n    # K=4 scales at \u03c6-ratio (Sargolini 2006; Stensola 2012) \u2014 provable\n    # length-OOD extrapolation. Activates the dormant code path; the\n    # 2K=8 raw features project to d_model via a zero-init head, so the\n    # first forward is bit-identical to baseline (Phase 1 contract).\n    grid_positions: { enabled: true, n_scales: 4, scale_ratio: 1.6180339887, base_period: 16.0 }\n    # HPB Phase 5: H19 local-context surprise head (Mismatch Negativity).\n    # Exposes per-token surprise = nll_local \u2212 nll_global on every\n    # train forward; harness logs it for diagnostics. Composes with\n    # H15's write gate when write_gate = \"surprise\".\n    surprise_head:  { enabled: true, dim: 128, local_window: 64 }\n    # HPB Phase 5: H15 episodic kNN memory (Memorizing Transformers /\n    # RETRO). Uniform writes (write_gate=\"all\") for the Phase-5\n    # baseline; surprise-gating + wake/sleep replay come in Phase 6.\n    # alpha_init=0 \u21d2 ReZero start: first forward bit-identical to\n    # baseline; the value blend only activates as \u03b1 lifts off zero\n    # under LM gradient pressure.\n    episodic_memory: { enabled: true, slots: 4096, k: 32, alpha_init: 0.0,\n                       write_gate: \"all\", write_quantile: 0.8 }\n    # HPB Phase 3 \u2014 Multi-Scale Predictive Coding Cascade.  Applies the\n    # MDRV-VBB free-energy at every adjacent layer pair (\u2113, \u2113+1) of the\n    # trunk, with geometric weight decay \u03bb_\u2113 = base_weight \u00b7 0.5^((L-1)-\u2113)\n    # so the deepest (bowtie waist) pair dominates and the shallowest\n    # pair contributes a small but non-zero compositional regulariser.\n    # Shares all VBB hyperparameters (alpha / free_bits / beta_max / eta).\n    # Composes additively with the single-waist VBB above.\n    mspcc: { enabled: true, base_weight: 0.02, layer_weight_decay: 0.5 }\n    # HPB Phase 4 \u2014 Hyperbolic Bowtie Waist (HBW). Curvature c=1.0 of\n    # the Poincar\u00e9 ball on which the VBB posterior is wrapped. The KL\n    # closed form picks up a Jacobian-log-det correction that strictly\n    # upper-bounds the Euclidean KL for any non-zero \u2016\u03bc\u2016 \u2014 making\n    # \u03c3-collapse harder by the construction of the geometry itself.\n    # Composes with all MDRV stabilisers (free-bits, \u03b2-ceiling, PEC).\n    vbb_curvature: 1.0\n    # \u2500\u2500 Multi-Trunk-v2: thalamic multi-cortex routing (see \u00a75.7) \u2500\u2500\n    # Four specialist language cortices (math / code / chat / general)\n    # mixed per token by neuroslm.cortex.ThalamicRouter.  The router\n    # combines a deterministic lexical-bias prior (`lexical_bias_weight`\n    # added to logits for the matching domain) with a zero-init\n    # learnable head (ReZero contract \u2014 at step 0, routing = pure\n    # lexical), and optionally damps per-batch oscillations through\n    # a BEMA running mean (`bema_tau`).\n    #\n    # Math (per token t in batch sample i, N = #cortices):\n    #     L_{ti} = beta * 1[x_{ti} in D] + W @ phi(x_{ti})\n    #     p_{ti} = softmax(L_{ti})                 in Delta^N\n    #     h_{ti} = sum_n p_{ti,n} * P_n(C_n(x))_{ti}\n    #\n    # At beta = lexical_bias_weight = 2.0 and N = 4 a token in domain\n    # d routes to cortex d with probability  e^2 / (e^2 + 3) ~ 0.730\n    # before any LM gradient lands (verified analytically in\n    # tests/test_ensemble_routing.py::test_pure_math_sequence_*).\n    #\n    # `weights` selects the production sub-cortex backend:\n    #     \"stub\" \u2014 random-init StubSubCortex (cold-start, no download)\n    #     \"gpt2\" \u2014 HuggingFace GPT-2 family, see DEFAULT_GPT2_VARIANTS\n    #              in neuroslm/cortex.py (gpt2-medium for math,\n    #              distilgpt2 for code, gpt2 for chat + general).\n    # `freeze_weights = true` keeps the GPT-2 backbones frozen and\n    # trains only the router + per-cortex projections in the cold-start\n    # phase.  Set to false to fine-tune all cortices end-to-end.\n    #\n    # \u2500\u2500 Mixture-of-Experts (`experts: [...]`) supersedes `weights:` \u2500\u2500\n    # Setting `experts: [...]` replaces the legacy single-`weights`\n    # field with an explicit per-expert roster. Each expert returns\n    # logits DIRECTLY in trunk-vocab space via its OWN pretrained LM\n    # head \u2014 bypassing the random Xavier `cortex_lm_head` projection\n    # that previously sat at the catastrophic `loss \u2248 ln(V)` ceiling\n    # (see scripts/diagnose_cortex_init.py for the in-vitro repro).\n    # When `experts:` is set, `n_cortices` and `domains:` are\n    # auto-derived from the roster (still listed below for human\n    # readability). See neuroslm/experts.py + tests/training/\n    # test_lm_expert_harness_integration.py for the smoking-gun CE\n    # contract (initial CE on natural English drops from ~10.85 to\n    # ~3-5 nats at step 0).\n    multi_cortex: {\n        enabled:             true,\n        n_cortices:          3,\n        domains:             [\"general\", \"code\", \"reasoning\"],\n        # Per-expert roster (new MoE path). Each row binds a HuggingFace\n        # model id to a routing domain. The expert's pretrained LM head\n        # produces trunk-vocab logits directly via VocabBridge \u2014 no\n        # random projection chain, no rogue-dim band-aid LayerNorm.\n        #\n        # 2026-06-14 (H22): the `general` slot was upgraded from `gpt2`\n        # (2019, ~125M params, WebText) to `smollm2_360m` (HuggingFaceTB\n        # /SmolLM2-360M \u2014 late-2024, ~360M params, 4T tokens of curated\n        # FineWeb-Edu + SmolLM-corpus + Cosmopedia). 3\u00d7 the parameters,\n        # ~100\u00d7 the training tokens, dramatically better per-parameter\n        # quality on natural English. Trade-off: SmolLM2 uses its own\n        # tokenizer (~49 152 BPE) \u2260 trunk's gpt2 tokenizer, so the\n        # `general` expert now traverses the VocabBridge path (per-sample\n        # retokenise + char-offset align) instead of the same-tokenizer\n        # fast path. With CodeGPT-small-py still on the gpt2 vocab, the\n        # ensemble is 1 fast-path + 2 bridge-path experts after the\n        # swap. The per-position abstain logic from H21 is what makes\n        # this safe \u2014 every cross-tok expert correctly fills unmapped\n        # trunk slots at the uniform baseline.\n        experts: [\n            { id: \"smollm2_360m\",               domain: \"general\",   freeze: true },\n            { id: \"microsoft/CodeGPT-small-py\", domain: \"code\",      freeze: true },\n            { id: \"Qwen/Qwen2.5-0.5B\",          domain: \"reasoning\", freeze: true }\n        ],\n        trunk_tokenizer:     \"gpt2\",\n        freeze_weights:      true,\n        lexical_bias_weight: 2.0,\n        bema_tau:            0.5,\n        router_d_model:      256,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Slot A: KL-distillation aux loss \u2500\u2500\n        # The trunk learns FROM the cortex by matching its full output\n        # distribution, not just argmax targets. \u03bb_t is a piecewise-\n        # linear ramp in the EMA gap (lm_loss - cortex_loss); when the\n        # trunk has caught up (gap \u2264 floor) distillation goes idle.\n        # See docs/formal_framework.md \u00a79 (admission criterion) and\n        # tests/training/test_cortex_distillation_and_gating.py.\n        distillation_enabled:      true,\n        distillation_lambda_max:   1.0,\n        distillation_temperature:  4.0,\n        distillation_gap_floor:    0.1,\n        distillation_gap_ceiling:  2.0,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Slot C: NT-mediated \u03b1 gating \u2500\u2500\n        # \u03b1_eff = \u03b1 \u00b7 (1 - cortex_inhibition_level). The inhibition\n        # level rises smoothly as the trunk outperforms the cortex\n        # (acts like a GABA-inhibitory NT released by the trunk into\n        # the cortex region). Once saturated near 1 the cortex\n        # contributes ~nothing and inference can skip the cortex\n        # forward entirely (~20\u00d7 FLOP savings at the rcc_bowtie_30m_p4\n        # scale).\n        inhibition_enabled:        true,\n        inhibition_ema_alpha:      0.05,\n        inhibition_temperature:    1.0,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Item 2 (Jun 2026): NE \u2192 router temperature \u2500\u2500\n        # The locus coeruleus (NE) is the brain's gain channel. With\n        # this gain > 0 the harness pushes the live NE level into the\n        # router each step; logits are multiplied by\n        #   mult = clamp(1 + k_NE\u00b7z_NE, 0.1, 10.0)\n        # before softmax. mult > 1 sharpens routing (winner-take-most),\n        # mult < 1 softens it. k_NE = 0.5 gives a \u00b150% logit-scale\n        # swing across NE \u2208 [0, 1], plenty to register without ever\n        # collapsing the softmax to a one-hot.\n        router_temp_nt_gain:       0.5,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Item 3 (Jun 2026): 5HT/DA \u2192 distillation \u03bb \u2500\u2500\n        # The gap-ramp \u03bb is multiplied by\n        #   nt_mult = clamp(1 + k_5HT\u00b7z_5HT \u2212 k_DA\u00b7z_DA, 0, 2)\n        # so the trunk LEANS HARDER on the cortex when 5HT is high\n        # (stress / conservatism \u2014 trust the teacher) and LESS when\n        # DA is high (reward / explore \u2014 go your own way). Identical\n        # gains (0.4) keep the two channels balanced; an asymmetric\n        # split would prejudge the policy.\n        distillation_5ht_gain:     0.4,\n        distillation_da_gain:      0.4,\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Item 4 (Jun 2026): GABA \u2192 lateral expert inhibition \u2500\u2500\n        # \u03ba_eff = \u03ba_base \u00b7 GABA. With \u03ba_base = 0.5 and GABA at its\n        # baseline (~0.15) the effective inhibition is ~0.075 \u2014 a\n        # gentle nudge toward specialisation that ramps as the\n        # homeostat raises GABA during high-ignition phases. The\n        # divisive normalisation is unconditionally on the simplex\n        # so the routing weights stay well-formed regardless of \u03ba.\n        lateral_inhibition_kappa:  0.5\n    }\n    # \u2500\u2500 Synthetic HPA axis \u2014 slow homeostatic stress damping \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n    # The existing neuromod stack has fast feedback (Homeostasis bumps\n    # GABA on grad spikes) but NO slow integrator. Result: NE can run\n    # away unchecked over ~40 steps (run 38470012: NE 0.20\u21920.93,\n    # gnorm 10\u219224, loss 12.6\u219215.4 between steps 460-500).\n    #\n    # `allostasis { ... }` adds the missing piece \u2014 a synthetic HPA\n    # axis with two state vars:\n    #   load(t) \u2014 fast EMA (\u03c4\u224810) of multi-modal stress (NE/GABA\n    #             excess, loss volatility, grad spikes), saturating.\n    #   cort(t) \u2014 slow EMA (\u03c4\u224834) of `load` \u2014 the cortisol integrator\n    #             that separates acute (single bad batch \u2014 leave alone)\n    #             from chronic (sustained \u2014 engage dampers).\n    #\n    # Three downstream multipliers, all in [0, 1] and applied each step:\n    #   ne_mult  = 1 - \u03b3_NE  \u00b7 cort  \u2192 caps NE release (closes the\n    #                                   LC positive-feedback loop)\n    #   troph_mult = 1 - \u03b3_T \u00b7 cort  \u2192 halts BDNF growth during crisis\n    #                                   (consolidate, don't sprout)\n    #   lr_mult  = 1 - \u03b3_LR \u00b7 cort   \u2192 damps optimizer LR (don't keep\n    #                                   updating chaotically)\n    #\n    # The 5\u00d7 HPA ratio (\u03b1_load=0.10, \u03b1_cort=0.02) makes brief spikes\n    # (1 bad batch + 99 calm) leave cort \u2248 0 \u2014 no damping for transient\n    # surprise \u2014 while sustained 200-step stress patterns drive cort\n    # past 0.25 where dampers begin to bite.\n    #\n    # See docs/findings.md H21 + tests/training/test_allostasis.py\n    # (38 contracts pinned including the smoking-gun replay of the\n    # actual 460\u2192500 runaway trajectory).\n    allostasis: {\n        enabled:           true,\n        load_ema_alpha:    0.10,\n        cort_ema_alpha:    0.02,\n        # Stress-source weights (sum to 1.0; the controller saturates\n        # the sum at 1 so this is bounded regardless).\n        w_ne:              0.30,\n        w_gaba:            0.20,\n        w_loss:            0.30,\n        w_grad:            0.20,\n        # Above-baseline thresholds (below these levels the channel\n        # contributes ZERO stress \u2014 tonic NT firing isn't pathological).\n        ne_baseline:       0.25,\n        gaba_baseline:     0.20,\n        grad_norm_ceiling: 5.0,\n        # All three effectors engaged. NE cap closes the runaway loop,\n        # trophic suppression stops growth during crisis, LR damping\n        # forces conservative updates instead of aggressive crisis-\n        # response weight changes (which is what diverged the run).\n        suppress_ne:       true,\n        suppress_trophic:  true,\n        suppress_lr:       true,\n        gamma_ne:          0.7,\n        gamma_trophic:     1.0,\n        gamma_lr:          0.5\n    }\n    # batch 16 x ctx 2048 = 32k tokens/step (same as old 32x1024) but\n    # ctx is 2x richer. The 32x2048 combo OOM'd on cross-entropy (13 GiB\n    # logit tensor at fp32). If you want to push back to batch=32, also\n    # port Brain's chunked CE (brain.py _chunked_ce) into the harness.\n    # ctx restored to 1024 + batch 32: throughput halved on ctx=2048\n    # (attention is O(seq^2)). Same 32k tok/step total, ~2x faster\n    # wall-clock. STACKED topology + dropout + pct carry the OOD wins;\n    # ctx-doubling was the lowest-impact regularizer in the original push.\n    # batch 16 x ctx 2048 = 32k tok/step (same total as prior 32x1024)\n    # but per-sequence context doubled. Long-range context matters for\n    # WikiText-103 OOD (academic prose has long-range deps). Throughput\n    # is 2x slower (attention O(seq^2)); proper fix would be to port\n    # Brain's chunked CE so we can run batch=32 ctx=2048 without OOM.\n    batch_size:   16\n    seq_len:      2048\n    steps:        40000\n    warmup_steps: 2400         # was 300 \u2014 scales with grad_accum=8 so we\n                                # still get 300 OPTIMIZER updates of warmup\n                                # (logged \"step\" counts micro-batches, not\n                                # opt updates). Prior 300 micro-batches =\n                                # 37 opt updates \u2192 too short, caused early\n                                # lurches at full LR.\n    min_lr_ratio: 0.1\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 C3 reentry as NT-gated trunk loss (Jun 2026) \u2500\u2500\n    # The PC reentry probe (predicting sensory hidden state from motor\n    # hidden state via a learned projection W) is no longer telemetry\n    # only \u2014 its residual is added to the LM loss, gradient flowing\n    # through BOTH populations so the trunk learns to make motor and\n    # sensory hidden states mutually predictive (a soft cycle-consistency\n    # / world-model constraint). Gating by neuromodulators:\n    #   gate = clip(1 + 0.5\u00b7DA \u2212 0.7\u00b7GABA, 0, \u221e)\n    # so the loss strengthens when DA is high (curiosity / reward) and\n    # weakens under GABA (cortical inhibition). eCB/5HT/Glu/etc. are\n    # left agnostic to avoid double-counting (they already modulate\n    # other parts of the homeostat).\n    pc_reentry_weight:  0.1\n    pc_reentry_nt_gate: true\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Item 6 (Jun 2026): trainable NT coupling matrix W \u2500\u2500\n    # When true, the DrivenNTSystem exposes its 7\u00d75 driver\u2192channel\n    # coupling matrix as an nn.Parameter (35 extra trainable scalars\n    # vs ~900M trunk + cortex params \u2014 negligible). The float OU\n    # dynamics in step_full() remain unchanged, so this flag never\n    # alters the numerical trajectory of `levels()` on its own.\n    # Gradient flows back to W_param only through differentiable\n    # downstream uses (router temperature, distillation \u03bb, lateral\n    # inhibition \u03ba) via predict_nt_tensor().\n    #\n    # SHIPPED DISABLED for the B5 sweep: Items 2/3/4 push float NT\n    # values into their consumers via plain dict `levels()`, which is\n    # all the optimisation signal we need to validate the GABA / NE /\n    # 5HT / DA mechanisms in isolation. Flipping this to `true` would\n    # add 35 trainable scalars whose gradient path is not yet wired\n    # to the consumers (would receive identically-zero grad \u2192 adds\n    # noise without learning signal). Re-enable once predict_nt_tensor\n    # is plumbed into the router / inhibition / distillation modules.\n    nt_w_trainable:     false\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Variational Bowtie Bottleneck (VBB) \u2014 Jun 2026 surgery \u2500\u2500\n    # The plain C3 PC-reentry residual was acting as a self-distillation\n    # amplifier: by step 4000 train ppl had halved (738\u2192426) while wiki\n    # ppl barely budged (3234\u21922899), pushing the gap ratio from 4.3 \u2192 6.8.\n    # VBB upgrades the residual into a Friston-style variational free\n    # energy at the bowtie waist:\n    #     L = \u03b3_NT \u00b7 ( \u03b2\u00b7\u2016s \u2212 W\u00b7(\u03bc + \u03c3\u00b7\u03b5)\u2016\u00b2 \u2212 log \u03b2 + \u03b1\u00b7KL[q \u2016 N(0,I)] )\n    # with q(h_m|x) = N(\u03bc, \u03c3\u00b2I), \u03bc = h_motor, log \u03c3\u00b2 = sigma_head(\u03bc).\n    # Three coupled mechanisms emerge:\n    #   1. KL[q \u2016 N(0,I)] is an Information Bottleneck at the narrowest\n    #      cross-section of the network \u2014 caps I(X; h_m), forbids\n    #      memorisation of training-distribution attractors.\n    #   2. \u03b2 = softplus(log_beta) self-throttles at \u03b2* = 1/(2\u00b7E[r]) via\n    #      the \u2212log \u03b2 log-normaliser. The loop stops being an amplifier\n    #      and becomes a calibrated generative model.\n    #   3. Reparam noise at the C3 read-site is structurally placed\n    #      stochastic gradient Langevin \u2014 biases SGD toward flat minima.\n    # Param overhead at d_sem=512: one Linear (262k) + one scalar = 0.21%.\n    # See harness._compute_pc_reentry_loss for the full math derivation.\n    vbb_alpha:     0.001\n    vbb_beta_init: 1.0\n    # \u2500\u2500 MDRV-VBB anti-collapse stabilisers (VBB-v2, Jun 2026) \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n    # Three interlocking mechanisms that prevent the \u03b2\u2191/\u03c3\u2193 co-collapse\n    # observed in the VBB-v1 run (gap 3.99\u21926.68 by step 4000):\n    #\n    #  1. Free-bits KL floor: guarantees \u22650.1 nats/dim of posterior\n    #     information \u2014 \u03c3\u21920 becomes provably non-optimal.\n    #  2. \u03b2-ceiling: clamps log \u03b2 \u2264 4.0 (\u03b2 \u2264 ~4.0) \u2014 breaks the\n    #     joint \u03b2\u2191/\u03c3\u2193 equilibrium that erased the bottleneck.\n    #  3. PEC (Posterior Entropy Commitment): Jeffreys prior on each\n    #     \u03c3_d \u2014 as \u03c3\u21920, PEC\u2192+\u221e, making collapse Lyapunov-unstable.\n    vbb_free_bits:    0.1\n    vbb_log_beta_max: 4.0\n    vbb_entropy_eta:  0.001\n    tonnetz_period: 0\n    bema_rollback_window: 0\n    bema_snapshot_every: 50\n    bema_cooldown: 100\n    nemori_floor: 0.0\n    mu_p_scaling: false\n    curriculum: \"random\"\n    crystallization_step: 0\n\n    # MAT-phase-gated mechanisms disabled for the 100M-genetics run.\n    # The MAT-ramp regularization was crippling early LM convergence\n    # (134M with phase-gated dropout active was 100+ ppl behind the 30M\n    # baseline at step 2500). Targets: loss<4, ppl<100 by step 10k \u2014\n    # pure-baseline trunk is closest to the 30M-on-30M run that hit\n    # them. Genetics still active but selected for LM-loss (below).\n    mechanisms: {}\n\n    # Declarative early-exit conditions. First rule to fire saves a\n    # checkpoint and exits the training loop. NOTE: only the \"OOD keeps\n    # falling\" rule is active \u2014 the step-thresholded fail-fast rules were\n    # removed (they were triggering on early-training noise).\n    #\n    # Rule: exit when OOD-ppl trend stalls. Compares min(OOD) in the first\n    # half of the window vs min(OOD) in the second half. Requires\n    # `min_evals` data points before it can fire, so transient single-eval\n    # noise (~3% on a 50-window WikiText eval) can't trigger exit on its\n    # own. `tol: 0.02` = require a real \u22652% improvement.\n    pass_marks: {\n        # Hard target: ppl < 100 at step 10k.\n        ppl_at_10k:   { metric: \"train_ppl\", at_step: 10000, max: 100 }\n        # OOD trend rule (loose \u2014 5 evals, 2% tol) as the success-exit.\n        ood_not_falling: {\n            metric: \"ood_ppl\",\n            window: 4000,\n            trend: \"falling\",\n            tol: 0.02,\n            min_evals: 5\n        }\n    }\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a76.5 Genetics \u2500\u2500\n    # optimize_for: \"lm_loss\" \u2014 genes train ONLY through the cortex's\n    # alpha_nt \u2192 LM gradient path. No -Phi aux term (phi_weight forced\n    # to 0). This avoids the prior failure mode where genes were pulled\n    # toward Phi-good but LM-bad configurations during early training,\n    # hurting the LM convergence rate.\n    # ReZero payload + alpha_nt=0 init means the cortex is bit-identical\n    # to baseline at step 0; the gate only opens if doing so reduces LM.\n    genetics: {\n        enabled:            true\n        n_genes:            32\n        d_pay:              16\n        optimize_for:       \"lm_loss\"\n        fixed_genes_preset: \"default\"\n        update_every:       4\n        diagnostics_every:  50\n    }\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Hardware envelope \u2500\u2500\n    # Deploy script filters vast.ai offers by these constraints.\n    # `dist_strategy`: \"single\" | \"ddp\" | \"fsdp\". Picked per scale below\n    # (large scales auto-override). Precision = bf16 (A100/H100 native).\n    # min_gpu_mem_gib: A100 SXM4 ships in 40 GB and 80 GB variants;\n    # without this filter vast.ai sometimes serves up tiny 16/20 GB\n    # MIG-sliced A100s ($0.7/hr range) that OOM at the first forward.\n    hardware: {\n        gpu_name:        \"A100_SXM4\"\n        num_gpus:        1\n        min_gpu_mem_gib: 40\n        min_reliability: 0.995\n        min_inet_mbps:   200\n        dist_strategy:   \"single\"\n        precision:       \"bf16\"\n    }\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Multi-scale variants of the same architecture \u2500\u2500\n    # Pick at deploy time via env SCALE=<name>. Each variant inherits\n    # the global `hardware` block unless it declares its own override.\n    # approx_params is informational (rough trunk-only count).\n    scales: {\n        default: \"30m_p4\"\n\n        30m_p4: {\n            d_model:       512\n            depth:         8\n            n_heads:       8\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    1       # T4 GPU memory: 16 GiB fits 1\u00d7512 ctx comfortably\n            seq_len:       512     # reduces attn memory (O(T\u00b2) per head); was 2048\n            grad_accum:    4       # compensates for batch=1; maintains training signal\n            approx_params: \"30M\"\n        }\n\n        # \u2500\u2500 Cheap-hardware 2k smoke run \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n        # Target: short (~2 hour) end-to-end smoke run on a $0.15-0.30/hr\n        # vast.ai instance \u2014 RTX 3090 / RTX 4090 / A5000 / RTX 4000 Ada.\n        # Used to verify that a DSL/DNA change boots cleanly + the MoE\n        # experts ensemble produces real loss before paying for full A100\n        # runs. NOT a research run; trajectories \u22642k steps are noise.\n        # Per CLAUDE.md \u00a710, even smoke runs are recorded as findings.\n        cheap_2k: {\n            d_model:       512\n            depth:         8\n            n_heads:       8\n            max_ctx:       1024   # 2\u00d7 the 30m_p4 ctx; still fits ~10 GiB\n            batch_size:    2      # double the signal/step of 30m_p4\n            seq_len:       1024\n            grad_accum:    2      # 4k tok/step \u2014 enough to dampen jitter\n            approx_params: \"30M\"\n            hardware: {\n                # RTX 3090 is the sweet spot: 24 GiB headroom for the\n                # 3 frozen MoE experts (~1.5 GiB fp16 each w/ activations),\n                # widely available at $0.15-0.25/hr; ~5x cheaper than A100.\n                gpu_name:        \"RTX_3090\"\n                num_gpus:        1\n                min_gpu_mem_gib: 20\n                min_reliability: 0.98\n                min_inet_mbps:   100\n                dist_strategy:   \"single\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n\n        100m: {\n            # Honest ~100M: trunk + embedding + lm_head \u2248 103M.\n            # (The previous 768/10 config was 204M because embedding +\n            #  lm_head + diff-block doublings added ~94M on top.)\n            # Layout: depth=8 with i%3 pattern \u2192 3 std + 3 diff + 2 mod\n            # blocks. 3 diff-attention blocks each need 2 \u00d7 (B, H, T, T)\n            # softmax tensors \u2014 at B=4 H=10 T=2048 bf16 that's ~1.6 GiB\n            # per block, ~5 GiB total. Comfortable on a 40 GiB A100.\n            d_model:       640\n            depth:         8\n            n_heads:       10\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    4\n            seq_len:       2048\n            grad_accum:    4\n            approx_params: \"~100M\"\n        }\n\n        300m: {\n            d_model:       1024\n            depth:         24\n            n_heads:       16\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    8\n            seq_len:       2048\n            grad_accum:    2\n            approx_params: \"300M\"\n            hardware: {\n                gpu_name:        \"A100_SXM4\"\n                num_gpus:        2\n                min_reliability: 0.995\n                min_inet_mbps:   200\n                dist_strategy:   \"ddp\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n\n        1b: {\n            d_model:       2048\n            depth:         24\n            n_heads:       16\n            max_ctx:       2048\n            batch_size:    4\n            seq_len:       2048\n            grad_accum:    4\n            approx_params: \"1B\"\n            hardware: {\n                gpu_name:        \"A100_SXM4\"\n                num_gpus:        4\n                min_reliability: 0.995\n                min_inet_mbps:   200\n                dist_strategy:   \"ddp\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n\n        7b: {\n            d_model:       4096\n            depth:         32\n            n_heads:       32\n            max_ctx:       4096\n            batch_size:    2\n            seq_len:       4096\n            grad_accum:    8\n            approx_params: \"7B\"\n            hardware: {\n                gpu_name:        \"H100_SXM\"\n                num_gpus:        8\n                min_reliability: 0.995\n                min_inet_mbps:   500\n                dist_strategy:   \"fsdp\"\n                precision:       \"bf16\"\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    # =========================================================================\n    # OOD INTERVENTIONS (regularization {})  \u2014 see docs/technical_report.md \u00a73\n    # Math-first definitions live in lib/regularizers.neuro.\n    #\n    # 2026-06-03 GROUND-TRUTH BASELINE\n    # \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n    # ALL interventions disabled. Four iterations of \"fixes\" (warmup ramp \u2192\n    # PR-A1 direction flip \u2192 neuromechanical stabilisation) each closed one\n    # failure mode and opened another. We never measured what vanilla\n    # training looks like at this scale, so we have no baseline to fix\n    # against. This run establishes that baseline.\n    #\n    # Re-enable individual interventions ONLY after we know what\n    # `wikitext gap_ratio` looks like with no interventions at chat_ratio\u22480.3.\n    # =========================================================================\n    regularization: {\n        # \u2500\u2500 WARMUP RAMP \u2014 REMOVED 2026-06-03 \u2500\u2500\n        # warmup_steps controlled a linear 0\u21921 ramp on all aux loss\n        # contributions. With every intervention disabled in this\n        # baseline config there is nothing to ramp, so the field has\n        # been removed to make the no-op explicit. When re-enabling\n        # any of (dar, pcc, isotropy, cmd, adaptive_mixture, cdga)\n        # restore `warmup_steps: 2000` here.\n\n        # A. Distributional Adversarial Reweighting \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        dar: { enabled: false, lambda: 1.0, hidden: 64, grl_alpha: 0.1,\n               weight: 0.1 }\n\n        # B. Predictive Contrastive Coding \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        pcc: { enabled: false, k: 4, n_negatives: 64, tau: 0.1, layers: [],\n               weight: 0.1 }\n\n        # C. Isotropy whitening \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        isotropy: { enabled: false, weight: 0.01, buffer: 4096, distance: \"frobenius\" }\n\n        # D. Cross-Module Disagreement \u2014 DISABLED (OOM at this batch+seq).\n        cmd: { enabled: false, weight: 0.05, divergence: \"jsd\",\n               heads: [\"lm\", \"narrative\"] }\n\n        # E. Adaptive mixture controller \u2014 DISABLED for baseline.\n        #    (The controller is architecturally blind to prose: it sees\n        #    entropy of the MIXED training batch, dominated by chat. It\n        #    cannot detect the prose-ppl collapse we observed at step\n        #    1000 of the previous run. Will be redesigned with a true\n        #    held-out probe before re-enabling.)\n        adaptive_mixture: { enabled: false, target_entropy: 4.5,\n                            probe_interval: 100, gamma: 2.0,\n                            direction: \"balance\",\n                            min_ratio: 0.10, max_ratio: 0.50,\n                            controller_warmup_steps: 2000,\n                            max_step_delta: 0.03,\n                            entropy_ema_alpha: 0.1 }\n\n        # F. Frequency-balanced cross-entropy \u2014 DISABLED (needs corpus scan).\n        freq_balance: { enabled: false, beta: 0.5,\n                        w_min: 0.2, w_max: 5.0 }\n\n        # G. Cross-Distribution Gradient Alignment (CDGA) \u2014 DISABLED\n        #    (research-grade, kept off until ground-truth baseline is\n        #    established and an anchor batch loader is wired in).\n        cdga: { enabled: false, alpha_max: 1.0,\n                warmup_steps: 2000, refresh_every: 4 }\n    }\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# PARAMETER SCOPES \u2014 declarative gradient isolation (the p3 architectural\n# fix). Bio-side populations are detached from the main LM loss; they're\n# driven by their own auxiliary objectives (Phase D), not by token CE.\n# The trunk carries the language-modeling gradient.\n# =============================================================================\n\nparam_scope trunk {\n    populations: [sensory, association, thalamus, world, self_m, qualia, gws, neural_geometry, entorhinal, pfc, acc, forward_m, evaluator, dmn, thought_transformer, claustrum, motor, reasoning_cortex, cortex_math, cortex_code, cortex_chat, cortex_general]\n}\n\nparam_scope bio {\n    populations: [amygdala, insula, hippo, cerebellum, bg, vta, nucleus_accumbens, locus_coeruleus, raphe_nuclei, nucleus_basalis, substantia_nigra],\n    gradient: \"detached_from_main_loss\"\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# NEUROTRANSMITTER SYSTEMS (7 classical) \u2014 globally visible\n# =============================================================================\n\nneurotransmitter dopamine {\n    base_concentration: 0.10,\n    release_rate: 0.20,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.80,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.02\n}\n\nneurotransmitter norepinephrine {\n    base_concentration: 0.15,\n    release_rate: 0.30,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.70,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.015\n}\n\nneurotransmitter serotonin {\n    base_concentration: 0.30,\n    release_rate: 0.05,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.95,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.01\n}\n\nneurotransmitter acetylcholine {\n    base_concentration: 0.20,\n    release_rate: 0.25,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.75,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.025\n}\n\nneurotransmitter endocannabinoid {\n    base_concentration: 0.05,\n    release_rate: 0.40,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.60,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.03\n}\n\nneurotransmitter glutamate {\n    base_concentration: 0.40,\n    release_rate: 0.50,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.50,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.02\n}\n\nneurotransmitter gaba {\n    base_concentration: 0.10,\n    release_rate: 0.10,\n    reuptake_rate: 0.90,\n    diffusion_rate: 0.01\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# LIBRARY IMPORTS \u2014 shared equations, constraints, regularization\n# =============================================================================\n\n# Canonical shared lib. The 3 standard equations live in @brian/equations\n# alongside the 5 feature-toggleable equations (hyperbolic_attention_eq,\n# rope_torus_eq, hrr_memory_eq, predictive_coding_residual_eq,\n# surprise_gated_moe_eq) \u2014 importing the whole shared registry from one\n# place avoids the local-shadow conflict that arose when both\n# `@/lib/equations` and `@brian/equations` resolved to the same bundled\n# `lib/equations.neuro` at unfold time and the local 3-symbol shadow\n# silently overwrote the canonical 8-symbol source of truth.\nimport { standard_synapse, multiplicative_modulation, additive_modulation } from \"@brian/equations\"\n# Regularizer & CDGA equation libraries \u2014 math-first declarative specs\n# for the OOD interventions (PR2 + PR-A + PR-B). The Python lowerings\n# live in neuroslm/regularizers.py and read their hyperparameters from\n# the `regularization { ... }` block above.\nimport { adaptive_mixture_update, freq_balance_loss, freq_balance_weight } from \"@/lib/regularizers\"\nimport { cdga_conflict_coef, cdga_aligned_gradient, cdga_strength_schedule } from \"@/lib/cdga\"\n\n# Emergent-topology library \u2014 math-first declarations for the six\n# closed-loop telemetry mechanisms (C1\u2013C6) introduced in RCC-Bowtie v2.\n# See docs/EMERGENT_TOPOLOGY.md for the design rationale. The Python\n# lowering lives in neuroslm/emergent/ and is wired into the metric\n# observer by default. Telemetry-only in this PR; promotion of any\n# mechanism into a forward-pass aux loss is a future PR.\nimport { nt_driver_standardise, nt_homeostat_step, nt_homeostat_readout } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { metastable_ignition_gate, metastable_ignition_event, metastable_threshold_update } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { pc_reentry_predict, pc_reentry_residual } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { topological_unit_field, topological_complex_pair, topological_phase_increment, topological_charge_total, topological_wall_indicator } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { lattice_slice_winner, lattice_specialisation_index } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\nimport { pac_bandpass_analytic, pac_phase_and_amplitude, pac_modulation_index } from \"@/lib/emergent\"\n\n# =============================================================================\n# TOGGLEABLE MECHANISMS (\u00a714 \u2014 declared inactive; activation = ablation)\n# =============================================================================\n# Five toggleable mechanisms from the shared @brian library. Each pairs\n# a real PyTorch impl (under neuroslm/modules/) with TDD-pinned math\n# contracts (under tests/). The feature blocks below import the\n# canonical equations + impl bindings; `active: false` keeps each one\n# bypassed at runtime so this baseline arch is byte-identical to the\n# pre-mechanism build. To run an ablation, copy-paste a feature block\n# below and flip `active: true` (and optionally tune its `params:`).\n#\n# See docs/features/<name>.md for hypothesis + math + wiring example.\nimport { hyperbolic_attention }          from \"@brian/features/hyperbolic_attention\"\nimport { rope_torus }                    from \"@brian/features/rope_torus\"\nimport { hrr_memory }                    from \"@brian/features/hrr_memory\"\nimport { predictive_coding_residual }    from \"@brian/features/predictive_coding_residual\"\nimport { surprise_gated_moe }            from \"@brian/features/surprise_gated_moe\"\n\n# =============================================================================\n# \u00a714 FEATURE ACTIVATION \u2014 flip mechanisms ON for this architecture\n# =============================================================================\n# Per CLAUDE.md \u00a714 the shared lib defines every feature with\n# `active: false` (clean baseline). The arch-local re-declarations\n# below override only the `active` flag \u2014 impl/params/endpoints are\n# inherited from the lib spec via the compiler's merge-by-name pass.\n# To run an ablation just delete (or comment out) the matching block\n# to revert that mechanism to its bypassed baseline.\n\nfeature hyperbolic_attention {\n    equation: hyperbolic_attention_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature rope_torus {\n    equation: rope_torus_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature hrr_memory {\n    equation: hrr_memory_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature predictive_coding_residual {\n    equation: predictive_coding_residual_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\nfeature surprise_gated_moe {\n    equation: surprise_gated_moe_eq,\n    active:   true\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# MODULE IMPORTS \u2014 every brain region this architecture comprises\n# =============================================================================\n\nimport { sensory, association }                          from \"@/modules/sensory\"\nimport { thalamus }                                       from \"@/modules/thalamus\"\nimport { world, self_m }                                  from \"@/modules/world\"\nimport { amygdala, insula }                               from \"@/modules/amygdala\"\nimport { qualia }                                         from \"@/modules/qualia\"\nimport { gws, neural_geometry }                           from \"@/modules/gws\"\nimport { hippo, entorhinal, cerebellum }                  from \"@/modules/hippocampus\"\nimport { pfc, acc }                                       from \"@/modules/pfc\"\nimport { bg, forward_m, evaluator }                       from \"@/modules/bg\"\nimport { dmn, thought_transformer, claustrum }            from \"@/modules/dmn\"\nimport { motor }                                          from \"@/modules/motor\"\nimport { vta, nucleus_accumbens, locus_coeruleus, raphe_nuclei, nucleus_basalis, substantia_nigra } from \"@/modules/nuclei\"\nimport { reasoning_cortex }                               from \"@/modules/reasoning_cortex\"\n# Multi-Trunk-v2 specialist language cortices \u2014 see Section 5.7 of\n# docs/architecture.md.  The dynamic per-token routing lives in\n# neuroslm/cortex.py (ThalamicRouter); the DSL declarations below\n# expose the four cortices to the analyser, the param_scope, and the\n# bowtie's synaptic wiring.\nimport { cortex_math, cortex_code, cortex_chat, cortex_general } from \"@/modules/cortex_specialists\"\n\n# =============================================================================\n# ANATOMICAL PROJECTIONS (cross-module synaptic wiring)\n# Equation: y = weight * (x_pre @ W) \u2014 PyTorch-batched linear projection.\n# =============================================================================\n\n# Thalamic gating (sensory bottleneck control)\nsynapse thalamus -> gws {\n    weight: 0.8, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Multi-Trunk-v2 thalamic routing (see \u00a75.7 of docs/architecture.md) \u2500\u2500\n# Four parallel projections from the thalamus to the specialist\n# language cortices.  Static `weight: 0.25` declares a uniform \u0394^4 prior\n# at the DSL level; the per-token, content-dependent weights are\n# computed at run-time by `neuroslm.cortex.ThalamicRouter` (lexical\n# bias + zero-init learnable head + optional BEMA biological damping)\n# and override these static priors during the forward pass.\n#\n# Mathematical contract (cf. Sherman & Guillery 2002, Halassa & Kastner\n# 2017): the thalamus is the brain's central gating bus; one synapse\n# per cortical specialist makes the gradient routing explicit, and\n# `param_scope trunk` keeps all four cortices on the language gradient.\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_math {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_code {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_chat {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse thalamus -> cortex_general {\n    weight: 0.25, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# State models \u2192 workspace\nsynapse world -> gws {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #4: predictive-coding residual \u2500\u2500\n    # World-model \u2192 conscious-workspace edge is the canonical sensory\n    # surface in PC (Rao-Ballard 1999). The trunk prediction g(x) is\n    # subtracted out; only the surprise (x - g(x)), scaled by alpha=0.1,\n    # propagates forward. See docs/features/predictive_coding_residual.md.\n    feature: \"predictive_coding_residual.edge\"\n}\nsynapse self_m -> gws {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# GWS \u2192 memory (every conscious access broadcasts to hippocampus)\nsynapse gws -> hippo {\n    weight: 0.7, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# GWS \u2192 cognitive control (top-down planning)\nsynapse gws -> pfc {\n    weight: 0.8, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #1: hyperbolic attention \u2500\u2500\n    # The semantic broadcast from the conscious workspace to executive\n    # control carries tree-shaped context (task hierarchy, plan\n    # subgoals); a Poincar\u00e9-disc metric (volume \u221d e^r) is the natural\n    # geometry. Ganea/B\u00e9cigneul/Hofmann 2018.\n    feature: \"hyperbolic_attention.edge\"\n}\nsynapse gws -> acc {\n    weight: 0.7, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# PFC \u2192 basal ganglia (action selection)\nsynapse pfc -> bg {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #5: surprise-gated MoE \u2500\u2500\n    # Action-selection cost should scale with how uncertain the policy\n    # is. SurpriseGatedMoE routes confident tokens to k_min=1 expert\n    # (cheap) and uncertain tokens to k_max=4 (rich mixture). Free-\n    # energy principle (Friston 2010) made concrete in compute budget.\n    feature: \"surprise_gated_moe.edge\"\n}\n\n# Basal ganglia \u2192 motor (action execution; GABAergic disinhibition)\nsynapse bg -> motor {\n    weight: 0.8, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Forward model + evaluator feedback\nsynapse forward_m -> evaluator {\n    weight: 0.7, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Memory feedback \u2192 PFC (recall-guided planning)\nsynapse hippo -> pfc {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #3: HRR-bound holographic memory \u2500\u2500\n    # The hippocampus-to-PFC recall edge is exactly the content-\n    # addressable retrieval HRR was invented for (Plate 1995). Per-batch\n    # memory M = \u03a3_t bind(k_t, v_t); per-token query unbinds the\n    # superposition.\n    feature: \"hrr_memory.edge\"\n}\nsynapse entorhinal -> pfc {\n    weight: 0.4, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Re-entry loop: PFC back to thalamus (bowtie closure \u2192 \u03a6 > 0)\nsynapse pfc -> thalamus {\n    weight: 0.3, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse,\n    # \u2500\u2500 \u00a714 mechanism #2: RoPE-on-Torus \u2500\u2500\n    # The bowtie closure carries iteration position around the re-entry\n    # loop \u2014 naturally cyclic, naturally multi-scale (token, episode,\n    # session). Per-slice torus periods (Su et al. 2024, generalised)\n    # encode this directly into the transmission.\n    feature: \"rope_torus.edge\"\n}\n\n# DMN \u2192 GWS (narrative broadcasts to conscious access)\nsynapse dmn -> gws {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# Cerebellum \u2192 forward model (classical conditioning, motor learning)\nsynapse cerebellum -> forward_m {\n    weight: 0.6, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# STACKED OOD TOPOLOGY (added after run 38569395 OOD gap_ratio 7.04)\n# Three independent mechanisms layered together. Surfaced by\n# `brian analyze rcc_bowtie --topo-10x`. Generalization proxy +63.5%.\n#\n#   1. PCT-style reentry: motor errors feed back to sensory.\n#      (matches B3 / PCT-30M from the OOD ablation arc which hit 4.51)\n#   2. MoE parallel path through reasoning_cortex (cuts OOD interference\n#      via specialised routing; lottery-ticket / sparse-routing lit).\n#   3. Lateral inhibition (GABA) between dmn and reasoning_cortex\n#      (sparse-coding effect: one specialised lane fires per token).\n# =============================================================================\n\n# (1) Reentry: deep motor -> sensory loop (closes the bowtie)\nsynapse motor -> sensory {\n    weight: 0.4, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# (2) MoE parallel path: pfc -> reasoning_cortex -> motor\nsynapse pfc -> reasoning_cortex {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse reasoning_cortex -> motor {\n    weight: 0.5, neurotransmitter: \"glutamate\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# (3) Lateral inhibition: dmn <-> reasoning_cortex (GABA)\nsynapse dmn -> reasoning_cortex {\n    weight: 0.3, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\nsynapse reasoning_cortex -> dmn {\n    weight: 0.3, neurotransmitter: \"gaba\",\n    equation: @standard_synapse\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# NEUROMODULATION (receptor banks \u2014 fast NT modulation of regions)\n# Equation: y = output * (c * gain)        for multiplicative effects\n# Equation: y = output + (c * gain)        for additive effects\n# c = NT concentration in nt_levels dict   gain = receptor sensitivity\n# =============================================================================\n\n# PFC \u2014 DA (motivation), 5HT (impulse control), ACh (attention), GABA (inhibition)\nmodulation dopamine -> pfc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.6,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation serotonin -> pfc {\n    effect: \"additive\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @additive_modulation\n}\nmodulation acetylcholine -> pfc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.4,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation gaba -> pfc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.4,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# Hippocampus \u2014 ACh (encoding), Glu (binding)\nmodulation acetylcholine -> hippo {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation glutamate -> hippo {\n    effect: \"additive\", gain: 0.4,\n    equation: @additive_modulation\n}\n\n# Basal ganglia \u2014 DA (motivation), GABA (competition)\nmodulation dopamine -> bg {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.7,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation gaba -> bg {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# Thalamus \u2014 NE (arousal), GABA (relay control)\nmodulation norepinephrine -> thalamus {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation gaba -> thalamus {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# Sensory \u2014 ACh (attention), eCB (inhibition)\nmodulation acetylcholine -> sensory {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation endocannabinoid -> sensory {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.3,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# DMN \u2014 5HT (introspection dampening), ACh (attention)\nmodulation serotonin -> dmn {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.6,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\nmodulation acetylcholine -> dmn {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.2,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# GWS \u2014 DA (salience boost)\nmodulation dopamine -> gws {\n    effect: \"additive\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @additive_modulation\n}\n\n# Amygdala \u2014 5HT (fear suppression via raphe)\nmodulation serotonin -> amygdala {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.7,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# ACC \u2014 DA (motivation)\nmodulation dopamine -> acc {\n    effect: \"multiplicative\", gain: 0.5,\n    equation: @multiplicative_modulation\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# FORMAL CONSTRAINT SYSTEMS \u2014 imported from lib/constraints.neuro\n# =============================================================================\n# Three core constraints that govern topology and ensure biological realism:\n#   1. Narrative Consistency (sheaf cohomology proxy for narrative coherence)\n#   2. Integrated Information (\u03a6 > 0 per Tononi 4.0 formalism)\n#   3. Bowtie Topology (narrowing-widening structure with re-entry)\n#\n# Math-first definitions live in lib/constraints.neuro. The linter verifies\n# these at compile time; the harness applies them as auxiliary losses at runtime.\n# =============================================================================\n\n# =============================================================================\n# THSD (Topological Hyper-Sheaf Dynamics) \u2014 Brain Regions as Simplicial Complexes\n# =============================================================================\n# Each brain region is formalized as a simplicial complex \u03c3\u1d48\u1d62 with:\n#   - SheafStalk: local representation space with Fisher information metric\n#   - Topology: Tonnetz manifold with spectral gap \u03bb\u2081 > 0.3\n#   - FormalSpec: cohomological constraints H\u00b9(K;F), \u03a6 maximization\n#   - Dynamics: vesicle-based mutations, NEMORI consolidation\n\n# Sensory input layer \u2014 thalamic gateway to conscious access\ncomplex Thalamus {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 256,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"predictive_consistency\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.32,\n        dimension: 6,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.95\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.005,\n        phi_target: 0.80,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\",\n        information_bottleneck: {\n            enabled: true,\n            compression_ratio: 0.7,\n            prediction_lower_bound: 0.92\n        }\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        emission {\n            trigger: \"surprise_head(threshold=0.8)\",\n            payload_dim: 64,\n            lifetime_steps: 100\n        },\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 1000,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.01\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# Global workspace (conscious space) \u2014 recurrent amplification & integration\ncomplex GlobalWorkspace {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 512,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"narrative_consistency\", \"gradient_stability\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.35,\n        dimension: 8,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.98\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.008,\n        phi_target: 0.85,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\",\n        information_bottleneck: {\n            enabled: true,\n            compression_ratio: 0.65,\n            prediction_lower_bound: 0.94\n        }\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        emission {\n            trigger: \"always\",\n            payload_dim: 96,\n            lifetime_steps: 150\n        },\n        release {\n            rule: \"rank_one_update\",\n            learning_rate: 0.001,\n            target: \"parameter_counts\"\n        },\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 800,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.005\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# Prefrontal cortex (executive control) \u2014 planning & decision-making\ncomplex PrefrontalCortex {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 384,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"planning_consistency\", \"value_alignment\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.33,\n        dimension: 7,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.96\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.006,\n        phi_target: 0.82,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\",\n        information_bottleneck: {\n            enabled: true,\n            compression_ratio: 0.72,\n            prediction_lower_bound: 0.93\n        }\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        emission {\n            trigger: \"surprise_head(threshold=0.7)\",\n            payload_dim: 80,\n            lifetime_steps: 120\n        },\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 900,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.008\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# Motor output layer \u2014 action generation\ncomplex MotorCortex {\n    stalk {\n        representation_dim: 192,\n        fisher_information_metric: \"information_geometry\",\n        local_constraints: [\"motor_smoothness\"]\n    },\n    topology {\n        kind: \"Tonnetz\",\n        spectral_gap: 0.30,\n        dimension: 5,\n        coherence_threshold: 0.94\n    },\n    formal_spec {\n        cohomology_floor: 0.004,\n        phi_target: 0.75,\n        phi_method: \"geometric_IIT4\"\n    },\n    dynamics {\n        nemori {\n            enabled: true,\n            consolidation_interval: 1200,\n            forgetting_floor: 0.012\n        }\n    }\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# TRIPLE GUARD \u2014 live admission gate for auto-evolution\n# =============================================================================\n# Normative reference: docs/formal_framework.md \u00a77.\n#\n# Every mutation proposed during training (rank-one DNA patches, structural\n# rewires, gene drifts) is gated by the (\u03a6 \u2227 H\u00b9 \u2227 \u03bb\u2081) admission criteria\n# below.  Mutations that *would* drive any of the three scores out-of-band\n# are dropped before they reach disk; rejected mutations are persisted to\n# a sibling `step_<N>.rejected.json` audit file so the human + the\n# evolutionary loop can both see what the architecture refused to become.\n#\n# The thresholds below are intentionally PERMISSIVE for pretraining (see\n# the \"PRETRAIN-FRIENDLY RECIPE\" note further up \u2014 early infancy must be\n# allowed to wander).  They are the *safety net*, not yet the *fitness\n# pressure*; tighten them after the trunk reaches its capacity ceiling.\n#\n#   phi_min     \u2014 minimum admissible \u03a6 after mutation; 0.0 disables.\n#   h1_max      \u2014 maximum admissible \u2016H\u00b9(K;F)\u2016 proxy; matches the default\n#                 hallucination_threshold in CohomologyValidator (5.0).\n#   lambda_min  \u2014 minimum admissible spectral-gap proxy \u03bb\u2081; 0.0 disables\n#                 until the \u00a74.2 Tonnetz Resonance Filter lands as a real\n#                 Laplacian computation.\n#\n# Code path: TripleGuard.from_arch_neuro(arch_path) reads this block;\n# EvolutionaryTrainingContext.set_triple_guard(guard) installs it; the\n# harness's mutation step then calls ctx.save_checkpoint(step, muts, pairs)\n# which routes through the guard.  See tests/training/test_rcc_bowtie_triple_guard.py\n# for the full contract.\nexport formal_spec triple_guard_admission {\n    rule: \"triple_guard\",\n    phi_min: 0.0,\n    h1_max: 5.0,\n    lambda_min: 0.0\n}\n\nimport { sheaf_narrative_consistency, formal_phi_integration, formal_bowtie_topology } from \"@/lib/constraints\"\n",
   "modules": {
    "@brian/equations": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\lib\\equations.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Shared equation library \u2014 reusable across every BRIAN architecture.\n#\n# Resolution: importable as `@brian/equations` from any arch.neuro.\n# Anchored at <repo>/architectures/lib/equations.neuro by the @brian/\n# prefix in neuroslm/dsl/multifile.py:PathResolver.\n#\n# Layout convention:\n#\n#   architectures/\n#       lib/\n#           equations.neuro            \u2190 this file (declarations only)\n#           features/\n#               <name>.neuro           \u2190 one file per toggleable mechanism\n#                                       declares: feature <name> { ... }\n#                                       imports: the equation it implements\n#                                       binds:   the Python impl class\n#       master/\n#           arch.neuro                 \u2190 imports `@brian/equations` + the\n#                                        features it wants exposed; wires\n#                                        them into synapses via `feature:`.\n#\n# Per CLAUDE.md \u00a714: every equation here MUST be backed by a real\n# implementation in neuroslm/modules/<name>.py and pinned by contract\n# tests in tests/test_<name>.py. The formula string is the mathematical\n# contract; the implementation must match.\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Canonical synapse transmission (default for every edge unless a\n# feature with `kind: \"edge\"` overrides it).\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nexport equation standard_synapse {\n    params: [weight, x_pre, W],\n    formula: \"y = weight * (x_pre @ W)\"\n}\n\n# Multiplicative modulation \u2014 e.g. dopamine/serotonin gain.\nexport equation multiplicative_modulation {\n    params: [output, c, gain],\n    formula: \"y = output * (c * gain)\"\n}\n\n# Additive offset \u2014 e.g. acetylcholine enhancing attention.\nexport equation additive_modulation {\n    params: [output, c, gain],\n    formula: \"y = output + (c * gain)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Feature-toggleable equations.\n#\n# Each equation below has:\n#   - a per-feature `.neuro` file under features/ that wires it to a\n#     Python impl class,\n#   - a real PyTorch module under neuroslm/modules/,\n#   - contract tests under tests/.\n#\n# Per CLAUDE.md \u00a710, adding/changing an equation here is a research\n# experiment: pair it with an Hxx hypothesis entry in docs/findings.md.\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\n# Mechanism 1: Hyperbolic (Poincar\u00e9-disc) multi-head attention.\n#\n# Ganea, B\u00e9cigneul, Hofmann \u2014 \"Hyperbolic Neural Networks\", NeurIPS 2018.\n# Q,K live on the Poincar\u00e9 ball with curvature c > 0; attention logits\n# are negative hyperbolic distances scaled by sqrt(head_dim); V stays\n# Euclidean (standard practice).\n#\n# Hypothesis: tree-shaped context (hierarchies, code AST, parse trees)\n# benefits from a metric whose volume grows exponentially with radius.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/hyperbolic_attention.py\n# Wiring:        @brian/features/hyperbolic_attention\n# Docs:          docs/features/hyperbolic_attention.md\n# Tests:         tests/test_hyperbolic_attention.py (18 contracts)\nexport equation hyperbolic_attention_eq {\n    params: [d_model, n_heads, c],\n    formula: \"Attn(Q,K,V) = softmax(-d_hyp(expmap0(Q), expmap0(K)) / sqrt(d_head)) @ V\"\n}\n\n# Mechanism 2: RoPE-on-a-Torus (multi-frequency rotary positional encoding).\n#\n# Su et al. \u2014 \"RoFormer\", Neurocomputing 568 (2024) \u2014 generalised to a\n# product-of-circles manifold T^n = (S^1)^n. Each 2D embedding slice\n# rotates by an angle whose period is drawn from a configurable schedule\n# (geometric/linear/harmonic). Positions wrap modulo each slice's\n# period \u2014 that's the torus part.\n#\n# Hypothesis: sequence position is cyclic at multiple scales (token,\n# sentence, paragraph); per-slice periods capture this directly.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/rope_torus.py\n# Wiring:        @brian/features/rope_torus\n# Docs:          docs/features/rope_torus.md\n# Tests:         tests/test_rope_torus.py (19 contracts)\nexport equation rope_torus_eq {\n    params: [d_model, base, schedule],\n    formula: \"RoPE(x, p) = R(\u03b8(p)) @ x where \u03b8_j(p) = 2\u03c0\u00b7(p mod period_j)/period_j\"\n}\n\n# Mechanism 3: Holographic Reduced Representations (HRR) memory.\n#\n# Plate (1995, 2003) \u2014 Compositional distributed representations via\n# circular convolution binding. Memory M = \u03a3 bind(k_i, v_i) is queried\n# by unbinding: unbind(M, k_j) \u2248 v_j + O(\u221a(N/d)) noise.\n#\n# Hypothesis: content-addressable memory with O(d log d) cost beats\n# softmax attention for long-range associative recall when the working-\n# set size N << d.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/hrr_memory.py\n# Wiring:        @brian/features/hrr_memory\n# Docs:          docs/features/hrr_memory.md\n# Tests:         tests/test_hrr_memory.py (16 contracts)\nexport equation hrr_memory_eq {\n    params: [d_model, d_memory],\n    formula: \"retrieve(x) = IFFT(\u03a3_t FFT(k_t) * FFT(v_t) * conj(FFT(q_x)))\"\n}\n\n# Mechanism 4: Predictive-coding residuals (Rao-Ballard 1999).\n#\n# Each layer predicts the layer below; only the residual \u03b5 = x - x\u0302\n# propagates upward. State update: x \u2190 x - \u03b1\u00b7\u03b5 (gradient on \u00bd\u03b5\u00b2).\n#\n# Hypothesis: explicit prediction errors make the trunk's information\n# flow sparser and the loss signal closer to the surprise-driven\n# updates predicted by free-energy formulations of cortex.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/predictive_coding_residual.py\n# Wiring:        @brian/features/predictive_coding_residual\n# Docs:          docs/features/predictive_coding_residual.md\n# Tests:         tests/test_predictive_coding_residual.py (14 contracts)\nexport equation predictive_coding_residual_eq {\n    params: [d_model, step_size],\n    formula: \"x' = x - \u03b1\u00b7(x - g(x))    where g is the top-down predictor\"\n}\n\n# Mechanism 5: Surprise-gated Mixture-of-Experts.\n#\n# Standard MoE (Shazeer 2017) routes each token to top-k experts. Here\n# k is dynamic per token: k(x) = round(k_min + (k_max-k_min)\u00b7\u03c3(steep\u00b7(s-mid)))\n# where s is the per-token surprise (gating entropy or supplied PC\n# residual norm). High surprise \u2192 more compute; low surprise \u2192 cheaper.\n#\n# Hypothesis: matches free-energy principle (Friston 2010) \u2014 surprise\n# drives compute allocation, like a soft early-exit / extra-think knob.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/surprise_gated_moe.py\n# Wiring:        @brian/features/surprise_gated_moe\n# Docs:          docs/features/surprise_gated_moe.md\n# Tests:         tests/test_surprise_gated_moe.py (20 contracts)\nexport equation surprise_gated_moe_eq {\n    params: [d_model, n_experts, k_min, k_max],\n    formula: \"MoE(x, s) = \u03a3_e top_w_e(x, k(s)) \u00b7 expert_e(x)\"\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@brian/equations"
    },
    "@/lib/regularizers": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\lib\\regularizers.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# lib/regularizers.neuro \u2014 math-first OOD intervention library\n#\n# Declarative equations for the five interventions proposed in\n# docs/technical_report.md \u00a73 (post-mortem of the gap_ratio regression).\n#\n# Each `equation` declares a closed-form loss term. The harness binds the\n# free symbols (h, p, etc.) to the appropriate tensors at runtime.\n# These are the *canonical* mathematical statements \u2014 the Python parser\n# in neuroslm/dsl/regularization.py exposes their hyperparameters.\n#\n# Conventions:\n#   h, h_t, h_pre, h_post  \u2014 hidden states (tensor, last dim = d_model)\n#   p, q                   \u2014 distributions over vocab (tensor, last dim = V)\n#   L_ce                   \u2014 per-sample cross-entropy losses (tensor [B])\n#   E[ \u00b7 ]                 \u2014 batch-mean expectation\n#   < \u00b7, \u00b7 >               \u2014 inner product\n#   ||\u00b7||_F                \u2014 Frobenius norm\n#   \u03c3                      \u2014 sigmoid; KL, JSD as standard\n#   GRL_\u03b1                  \u2014 gradient reversal layer with scale \u03b1\n#\n# IMPORTANT: these equations are research-grade specifications. The\n# codegen lowers them through neuroslm/dsl/regularization.py for now;\n# PR4 will add a generic `optimization_problem` lowerer so new losses\n# can be added without touching Python.\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Intervention A \u2014 Distributional Adversarial Reweighting \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\nexport equation dar_discriminator {\n    params: [h, W_d, b_d, alpha],\n    formula: \"y = sigmoid(GRL(h, alpha) @ W_d + b_d)\"\n}\n\nexport equation dar_loss {\n    params: [L_ce, d_pred, domain_label, lam, minority_mask],\n    formula: \"y = mean(exp(lam * L_ce * minority_mask) * L_ce) + BCE(d_pred, domain_label)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Intervention B \u2014 Predictive Contrastive Coding \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Replaces the reconstructive PCT loss. Forces deep layers to encode\n# features predictive of future context while remaining invariant to\n# document-specific surface form (negatives come from other documents).\n\nexport equation pcc_anchor {\n    params: [h_t, W_proj],\n    formula: \"y = h_t @ W_proj\"\n}\n\nexport equation pcc_loss {\n    params: [z_anchor, z_positive, z_negatives, tau],\n    formula: \"y = -log(exp(<z_anchor, z_positive> / tau) / (exp(<z_anchor, z_positive> / tau) + sum(exp(<z_anchor, z_negatives> / tau))))\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Intervention C \u2014 Isotropy whitening \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Pushes the empirical Gram matrix toward I, killing the \"narrow cone\"\n# anisotropy that mediates OOD gap in transformer LMs.\n\nexport equation isotropy_gram {\n    params: [H_buf, N],\n    formula: \"G = (H_buf.T @ H_buf) / N\"\n}\n\nexport equation isotropy_loss_frobenius {\n    params: [G, d],\n    formula: \"L = ||G - I||_F^2 / (d * d)\"\n}\n\nexport equation isotropy_loss_log_det {\n    params: [G],\n    formula: \"L = -log(det(G))\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Intervention D \u2014 Cross-Module Disagreement \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Two read-out heads produce vocab distributions p, q; we penalize their\n# JSD. Shared signal between modules is OOD-robust; idiosyncratic\n# disagreement is the shortcut and gets punished.\n\nexport equation cmd_mean_distribution {\n    params: [p, q],\n    formula: \"m = 0.5 * (p + q)\"\n}\n\nexport equation cmd_loss_jsd {\n    params: [p, q, m, weight],\n    formula: \"L = weight * (0.5 * KL(p, m) + 0.5 * KL(q, m))\"\n}\n\nexport equation cmd_loss_kl_sym {\n    params: [p, q, weight],\n    formula: \"L = weight * (0.5 * KL(p, q) + 0.5 * KL(q, p))\"\n}\n\nexport equation cmd_loss_l1 {\n    params: [p, q, weight],\n    formula: \"L = weight * mean(|p - q|)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Intervention E \u2014 Adaptive mixture controller \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Closed-loop control rule: re-weights the corpus mixture every K steps\n# based on measured logit entropy on a held-out prose probe.\n\nexport equation probe_entropy {\n    params: [p_probe],\n    formula: \"H = -mean(sum(p_probe * log(p_probe)))\"\n}\n\n# Adaptive mixture controller \u2014 corrected (entropy-parity) direction.\n#\n# Intuition: H_t is the measured entropy on a held-out PROSE probe.\n# If H_t > H_target the model is *uncertain* on prose \u2192 it has seen\n# too little of that distribution \u2192 the controller must dial CHAT\n# DOWN (more prose exposure). If H_t < H_target the model is fluent\n# on prose \u2192 it has spare capacity for chat \u2192 chat ratio can grow.\n#\n# The original `(H_t / H_target)^gamma` formula was BACKWARDS: it\n# *amplified* whichever distribution the model already overfit to,\n# producing the runaway 0.60 \u2192 0.80 chat_ratio observed in the\n# 2026-06-03 trace where gap_ratio widened monotonically.\n#\n# The `direction` parameter selects the rule:\n#   direction = \"balance\"  \u2192  (H_target / H_t)^gamma    (DEFAULT, correct)\n#   direction = \"amplify\"  \u2192  (H_t / H_target)^gamma    (legacy bug \u2014 kept\n#                                                        for ablation only)\n\nexport equation adaptive_mixture_update {\n    params: [chat_ratio_t, H_t, H_target, gamma, r_min, r_max, direction],\n    formula: \"chat_ratio_next = clip(chat_ratio_t * (direction == \\\"balance\\\" ? (H_target / H_t)^gamma : (H_t / H_target)^gamma), r_min, r_max)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Intervention F \u2014 Frequency-balanced cross-entropy \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Token-level inverse-frequency reweighting toward an OOD target\n# corpus. Pre-computed unigram frequencies on both train and target\n# corpora produce a per-vocab weight vector that downweights tokens\n# the train corpus over-represents relative to the OOD target.\n#\n# Math (cf. focal loss, class-balanced loss [Cui et al. 2019]):\n#\n#   freq_train[v]   = count_v / \u03a3_v count_v       (over training sample)\n#   freq_target[v]  = count_v / \u03a3_v count_v       (over OOD probe sample)\n#   ratio[v]        = freq_target[v] / (freq_train[v] + \u03b5)\n#   w[v]            = clip(ratio[v]^beta, w_min, w_max)\n#   w[v]            = w[v] / mean(w[v])           (mean-normalised so\n#                                                  the loss scale is\n#                                                  unchanged \u2014 only the\n#                                                  *direction* per token)\n#   L_freq          = mean( w[ targets ] * CE_per_token )\n#\n# \u03b2 controls the strength: 0 = uniform (identity), 1 = exact inverse\n# frequency, 0.5 = square-root smoothing (Mikolov 2013-style).\n# Recommended \u03b2 = 0.5, w_max = 5.0, w_min = 0.2 \u2014 keeps the loss\n# scale within 5\u00d7 of the baseline so the LR schedule still works.\n\nexport equation freq_balance_weight {\n    params: [freq_train, freq_target, beta, w_min, w_max],\n    formula: \"w[v] = clip((freq_target[v] / (freq_train[v] + epsilon))^beta, w_min, w_max)\"\n}\n\nexport equation freq_balance_normalize {\n    params: [w],\n    formula: \"w_norm[v] = w[v] / mean(w[v])\"\n}\n\nexport equation freq_balance_loss {\n    params: [CE_per_token, targets, w_norm],\n    formula: \"L = mean( w_norm[ targets ] * CE_per_token )\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 PCT-IB (proposed, lands in PR3) \u2014 multi-scale predictive coding \u2500\u2500\n# Information-bottleneck variant of PCT. Replaces ||\u0125_n - h_n||^2 with\n# a stochastic latent + KL penalty + shortcut-orthogonal projection.\n# Currently declared for documentation; codegen lowering in PR3.\n\nexport equation pct_ib_latent {\n    params: [h_post, encoder_mu, encoder_sigma, epsilon],\n    formula: \"z = encoder_mu(h_post) + epsilon * encoder_sigma(h_post)\"\n}\n\nexport equation pct_ib_loss {\n    params: [h_pre, h_pre_hat, P_perp, mu, sigma, beta],\n    formula: \"L = ||P_perp @ (h_pre - h_pre_hat)||_F^2 + beta * KL(N(mu, sigma^2), N(0, 1))\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Constraints \u2014 provide solver hints for the analyzer \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\nformal_spec dar_objective {\n    rule: \"domain_adversarial_invariance\",\n    metric: \"domain_classification_acc_target = 0.5\"\n}\n\nformal_spec isotropy_objective {\n    rule: \"rank_preservation\",\n    metric: \"effective_rank(G) -> d\"\n}\n\nformal_spec pcc_objective {\n    rule: \"infomax_with_invariance\",\n    metric: \"I(z_t; z_{t+k}) under cross_document_negatives\"\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/lib/regularizers"
    },
    "@/lib/cdga": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\lib\\cdga.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# lib/cdga.neuro \u2014 Cross-Distribution Gradient Alignment (CDGA)\n#\n# Math-first specification of the gradient-surgery mechanism that\n# resolves the gap_ratio regression observed in the 2026-06-03 trace.\n#\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# WHY THIS EXISTS\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# All five PR2 OOD interventions (DAR, PCC, Isotropy, CMD, Adaptive\n# Mixture) operate in LOSS space \u2014 they add scalar penalties that\n# nudge the model away from collapse modes. Empirically they leave\n# the gap_ratio widening (train_ppl 1926 \u2192 872 while wiki_ppl stayed\n# at 7000+, gap_ratio 4.0 \u2192 7.4 over 500 steps).\n#\n# Diagnosis: the loss-space tools are isotropic in parameter space.\n# When the data distribution is dominated by one mode (chat 80%) the\n# vanilla LM gradient still points into the chat-attractor basin\n# every step; defensive regularizers add friction but no direction.\n# What is missing is an ANISOTROPIC, OOD-AWARE gradient signal.\n#\n# CDGA supplies it by maintaining a frozen anchor batch of pure OOD\n# (prose) tokens and projecting out the component of the training\n# gradient that would actively HURT the anchor.\n#\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# MATHEMATICAL FORMULATION\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Let \u03b8 be the trainable parameters and L the standard LM loss.\n# At step t the harness computes two gradients on the same \u03b8:\n#\n#     g_train  = \u2207_\u03b8 L(x_train; \u03b8)        # standard step, retained\n#     g_anchor = \u2207_\u03b8 L(x_anchor; \u03b8)        # OOD reference, discarded\n#                                          # after projection\n#\n# `x_anchor` is a held-out PROSE batch refreshed every `refresh_every`\n# steps from a separate corpus partition that NEVER overlaps with the\n# OOD evaluation slice (no test contamination \u2014 see formal_spec at the\n# end of this file).\n#\n# Compute the inner product and the cosine:\n#\n#     dot       = <g_train, g_anchor>\n#     g2        = <g_anchor, g_anchor>            ( = ||g_anchor||\u00b2 )\n#     cos_\u03b8     = dot / (||g_train|| \u00b7 \u221ag2)\n#\n# The CONFLICT COEFFICIENT is the negative projection coefficient,\n# rectified to be active only when the gradients oppose:\n#\n#     c = max(0, -dot / g2)                        # \u2265 0\n#\n# (When dot \u2265 0 the gradients are aligned or orthogonal \u2014 no surgery\n# needed. When dot < 0 the training step would actively worsen the\n# anchor loss; c quantifies by how much, in units of ||g_anchor||.)\n#\n# The aligned gradient subtracts the conflict component, scaled by\n# the global strength \u03b1 \u2208 [0, 1]:\n#\n#     g_aligned = g_train - \u03b1 \u00b7 c \u00b7 g_anchor\n#\n# This is the same projection operator as PCGrad (Yu et al. 2020) but\n# applied between a single LM task evaluated on TWO distributions,\n# rather than between distinct multi-task objectives.\n#\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# PROPERTIES (proved in docs/CDGA.md)\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# (P1) Non-worsening anchor: when \u03b1 = 1 and c > 0, the first-order\n#      expected change in L(x_anchor) is non-positive. The training\n#      step cannot increase anchor loss to first order.\n# (P2) Bounded perturbation: ||g_aligned - g_train|| = \u03b1 \u00b7 c \u00b7 ||g_anchor||\n#      \u2264 \u03b1 \u00b7 ||g_train|| \u00b7 |cos_\u03b8| \u2264 \u03b1 \u00b7 ||g_train||. So CDGA never\n#      changes the gradient by more than the training gradient itself.\n# (P3) Idempotent on aligned tasks: when dot \u2265 0 the operator is a no-op.\n# (P4) Warmup-safe: applying the standard `warmup_steps` ramp to \u03b1\n#      ensures CDGA only engages once the LM has formed baseline\n#      features (otherwise both gradients are random noise and\n#      surgery is meaningless).\n#\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# IMPLEMENTATION CONTRACT\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# The Python implementation in neuroslm/regularizers.py :: CDGAController\n# realises these equations against PyTorch parameter `.grad` tensors:\n#\n#   1. After the standard backward() the harness owns g_train in p.grad\n#      for every trainable p.\n#   2. CDGAController.apply_surgery(model, anchor_batch_fn):\n#        a. Snapshot g_train as a flat vector (or per-parameter list).\n#        b. Zero grads, forward+backward on the anchor batch \u2192 g_anchor\n#           in p.grad.\n#        c. Compute dot, g2, c, \u03b1 scalars.\n#        d. Write g_aligned = g_train - \u03b1\u00b7c\u00b7g_anchor back into p.grad.\n#   3. Optimizer.step() proceeds normally with the aligned gradients.\n#\n# Cost: one extra forward+backward every `refresh_every` steps. With\n# a 1/4-size anchor batch (e.g. 1 \u00d7 512 tok vs 4 \u00d7 2048 tok) the\n# overhead is \u2248 8% of one full training step amortised across the\n# refresh interval.\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Core equations \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\nexport equation cdga_inner_product {\n    params: [g_train, g_anchor],\n    formula: \"dot = <g_train, g_anchor>\"\n}\n\nexport equation cdga_conflict_coef {\n    params: [g_train, g_anchor],\n    formula: \"c = max(0, - <g_train, g_anchor> / <g_anchor, g_anchor>)\"\n}\n\nexport equation cdga_aligned_gradient {\n    params: [g_train, g_anchor, c, alpha],\n    formula: \"g_aligned = g_train - alpha * c * g_anchor\"\n}\n\n# Cosine similarity is published as a telemetry metric so that runs\n# can be diagnosed: a healthy training run shows cos_\u03b8 > 0 after\n# warmup (train and prose gradients aligned). A monotonically\n# decreasing cos_\u03b8 signals the chat-attractor pulling away from the\n# prose manifold \u2014 the failure mode CDGA is designed to interrupt.\n\nexport equation cdga_cosine_similarity {\n    params: [g_train, g_anchor],\n    formula: \"cos_theta = <g_train, g_anchor> / (||g_train|| * ||g_anchor||)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Schedule for the global strength \u03b1 \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Linear ramp from 0 to alpha_max over `warmup_steps`. After warmup,\n# \u03b1 stays at alpha_max. Setting alpha_max = 0 disables CDGA without\n# removing the telemetry pass (still computes cos_\u03b8 for diagnostics).\n\nexport equation cdga_strength_schedule {\n    params: [step, warmup_steps, alpha_max],\n    formula: \"alpha = min(alpha_max, alpha_max * step / warmup_steps)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500 Anchor batch refresh schedule \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Pure-prose anchor token IDs are sampled from the OOD corpus\n# partition once every `refresh_every` steps. Between refreshes the\n# same anchor batch is reused (which is fine because we use it only\n# for gradient direction, not for parameter updates \u2014 staleness costs\n# at most a slight bias in the projection direction).\n\nexport equation cdga_anchor_refresh {\n    params: [step, refresh_every],\n    formula: \"is_refresh_step = (step mod refresh_every == 0)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# FORMAL SPECIFICATIONS \u2014 analyser hints\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\nformal_spec cdga_test_contamination {\n    rule:   \"anchor_corpus_disjoint_from_eval\",\n    metric: \"intersect(anchor_doc_ids, ood_eval_doc_ids) = empty\"\n}\n\nformal_spec cdga_non_worsening {\n    rule:   \"first_order_anchor_loss_non_increasing\",\n    metric: \"E[ <\u2207L_anchor, g_aligned> ] \u2264 E[ <\u2207L_anchor, g_train> ]\"\n}\n\nformal_spec cdga_bounded_perturbation {\n    rule:   \"gradient_perturbation_bounded_by_training_gradient\",\n    metric: \"||g_aligned - g_train|| \u2264 alpha_max * ||g_train||\"\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/lib/cdga"
    },
    "@/lib/emergent": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\lib\\emergent.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# lib/emergent.neuro \u2014 math-first declarations for the six mechanisms\n# (C1\u2013C6) that turn the dead biology of the original RCC-Bowtie into\n# closed-loop, signal-bearing measurements.\n#\n# Each `equation` here is the *canonical* mathematical statement of one\n# mechanism. The Python lowering lives under `neuroslm/emergent/` and\n# is wired into `dsl.metrics.MetricObserver(enable_emergent=True)` by\n# default. See `docs/EMERGENT_TOPOLOGY.md` for the full design rationale\n# and falsifiable predictions per mechanism.\n#\n# Conventions (in addition to those of lib/regularizers.neuro):\n#   h, h_t         \u2014 per-token hidden states (tensor, last dim = d_model)\n#   \u0125_t            \u2014 unit-normalised hidden state, \u0125_t = h_t / ||h_t||\n#   L_t            \u2014 instantaneous LM loss at step t\n#   g_t            \u2014 instantaneous gradient L2 norm at step t\n#   E_w[\u00b7]         \u2014 EMA over window w\n#   \u03c3              \u2014 sigmoid; atan2 \u2014 standard four-quadrant arctangent\n#   R \u2208 so(d)      \u2014 fixed skew-symmetric chirality operator (seed-stable)\n#   <\u00b7,\u00b7>          \u2014 inner product\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# C1 \u2014 Driven neuromodulators (homeostatic field)\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# The seven classical NT channels are realised as ONE leaky-linear\n# (Ornstein\u2013Uhlenbeck) dynamical system in unbounded logit space y\u2208\u211d\u2077,\n# driven by standardised training-state scalars and read out through a\n# single sigmoid.  This formulation inherently prevents the rail-clip\n# (eCB, Glu, ACh), one-way ratchet (5HT) and stuck-at-zero (GABA)\n# pathologies of per-channel feedforward squashes:\n#   \u2022 drivers z-scored \u21d2 \u03c3 stays in its responsive region;\n#   \u2022 \u03b1>0 leak \u21d2 guaranteed recovery from any excursion;\n#   \u2022 single \u03c3 at readout \u21d2 nt\u2208(0,1) open interval.\n\nexport equation nt_driver_standardise {\n    # Per-driver z-score against running EMA mean/std (Welford-on-EMA).\n    # alpha_d \u2248 0.02 \u21d2 ~50-step memory; warmup-suppressed (z=0 for n<5).\n    params: [d_k, mu_d_k, var_d_k, eps],\n    formula: \"z_k = (d_k - mu_d_k) / sqrt(var_d_k + eps)\"\n}\n\nexport equation nt_homeostat_step {\n    # Leaky linear OU step.  W \u2208 \u211d^{7\u00d75} couples K=5 standardised\n    # drivers (surprise, gnorm, activation, ignition, attn_sharp) to\n    # the 7 channels (DA, NE, 5HT, ACh, eCB, Glu, GABA).  \u03b1 \u2208 \u211d^7 is\n    # the per-channel leak rate; \u03bc = logit(baseline) is the tonic\n    # resting logit.\n    params: [y_prev, alpha, mu, W, z],\n    formula: \"y_next = (1 - alpha) * y_prev + alpha * (mu + W @ clip(z, -5, 5))\"\n}\n\nexport equation nt_homeostat_readout {\n    # Single squash at readout \u2014 the only place \u03c3 is applied, so it\n    # always operates in its responsive central region.\n    params: [y],\n    formula: \"nt = sigmoid(y)\"\n}\n\nformal_spec nt_homeostat_stationarity {\n    statement: \"For fixed driver statistics, the channel vector y is OU with stationary distribution N(mu + W*z_bar, alpha/(2-alpha) * W Sigma_z W^T); nt = sigma(y) is therefore in (0,1) almost surely\",\n    proof_hint: \"Standard linear-Gaussian SDE result; each channel is an independent leaky integrator of a bounded stationary input.\"\n}\n\nformal_spec nt_homeostat_recovery {\n    statement: \"Each channel exponentially relaxes to sigma(mu_c) with time constant 1/alpha_c when its drivers vanish\",\n    proof_hint: \"Setting z=0 reduces the OU step to y_next = (1-alpha) y_prev + alpha mu, geometric convergence to mu in logit space.\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# C2 \u2014 Metastable ignition (event-detector with adaptive threshold)\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Replaces the always-on `gws_ignition` peakiness metric with a true\n# event model: ignition fires only when the workspace peak crosses a\n# self-regulating threshold that targets \u03c1* = 0.2.\n\nexport equation metastable_ignition_gate {\n    # Sigmoid-gated continuous strength; NE lowers the effective\n    # threshold (high arousal \u2192 easier to ignite).\n    params: [peak_t, theta_t, NE, beta, tau_soft],\n    formula: \"g_t = sigmoid((peak_t - theta_t - beta * NE) / tau_soft)\"\n}\n\nexport equation metastable_ignition_event {\n    # Discrete event indicator.\n    params: [g_t, p_star],\n    formula: \"e_t = step(g_t - p_star)\"\n}\n\nexport equation metastable_threshold_update {\n    # Proportional controller \u2014 drives mean event rate toward target \u03c1*.\n    params: [theta_t, e_recent_mean, rho_target, eta],\n    formula: \"theta_{t+1} = clip(theta_t + eta * (e_recent_mean - rho_target), 0, 1)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# C3 \u2014 Predictive-coding reentry residual (motor \u2192 sensory)\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Tests Friston-style free-energy minimisation on the bowtie's existing\n# motor \u2192 sensory feedback synapse. The predictor is isolated (no\n# gradient leaks into the trunk in this phase) so the residual is a\n# pure observation; promotion to a `\u03bb_pc \u00b7 \u2016e\u2016\u00b2` aux loss is Phase 8.\n\nexport equation pc_reentry_predict {\n    # Diagonal + rank-1 predictor: \u015d_t = diag(d) \u00b7 m_{t-1} + (m\u00b7v) u\n    params: [m_prev, d_diag, u, v],\n    formula: \"s_hat = (m_prev * d_diag) + (<m_prev, v>) * u\"\n}\n\nexport equation pc_reentry_residual {\n    # Prediction error at sensory layer; we report its squared norm.\n    params: [s_t, s_hat],\n    formula: \"e_t = s_t - s_hat\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# C4 \u2014 Topological charge Q (the skyrmion analog)\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Discrete winding number of the unit-norm hidden field along the token\n# axis under a fixed skew operator R. Conserved-charge structure on top\n# of the residual stream; cannot be smoothly destroyed without crossing\n# a \"domain wall\" (a token where <h_t, h_{t+1}> < 0).\n#\n# This is the *core* of the RCC-Bowtie v2 phenomenology: plateaus of Q\n# correspond to discourse-coherent spans; walls align with semantic\n# boundaries.\n\nexport equation topological_unit_field {\n    # Normalise to the unit sphere S^{d-1}.\n    params: [h_t],\n    formula: \"h_hat_t = h_t / max(||h_t||, eps)\"\n}\n\nexport equation topological_complex_pair {\n    # Re + i\u00b7Im decomposition of adjacent unit-vectors under R.\n    params: [h_hat_t, h_hat_tp1, R],\n    formula: \"z_t = <h_hat_t, h_hat_tp1> + i * <h_hat_t, R @ h_hat_tp1>\"\n}\n\nexport equation topological_phase_increment {\n    # Per-step phase via four-quadrant atan2.\n    params: [z_t],\n    formula: \"d_phi_t = atan2(Im(z_t), Re(z_t))\"\n}\n\nexport equation topological_charge_total {\n    # Conserved winding number along the sequence; integer plateaus\n    # emerge naturally when the field is structured.\n    params: [d_phi],\n    formula: \"Q = (1 / (2 * pi)) * sum_t(d_phi_t)\"\n}\n\nexport equation topological_wall_indicator {\n    # Domain-wall mask: a wall occurs where adjacent unit-vectors are\n    # anti-correlated. Wall count = discrete jumps in Q.\n    params: [h_hat_t, h_hat_tp1],\n    formula: \"wall_t = step(-<h_hat_t, h_hat_tp1>)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# C5 \u2014 Bowtie-lattice specialisation index (mixture-of-bowties probe)\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# Probe whether a single d-dim workspace already partitions latently\n# into K specialised lanes. Lift = max-class conditional probability\n# divided by marginal; averaged over slices. S = 1 \u21d2 no specialisation;\n# S = #classes \u21d2 perfect one-class-per-lane.\n\nexport equation lattice_slice_winner {\n    # WTA across K equal-width slices of the workspace activation.\n    params: [h, K, slice_size],\n    formula: \"k_star = argmax_k ||h[:, k*slice_size:(k+1)*slice_size]||\"\n}\n\nexport equation lattice_specialisation_index {\n    # Mean per-slice maximum class lift. Bounded below by 1.\n    params: [P_c_given_k, P_c],\n    formula: \"S = (1/K) * sum_k max_c (P_c_given_k / P_c)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# C6 \u2014 Phase-amplitude coupling (PAC) binding\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# The Tort modulation index over a rolling buffer of the same signal\n# that drives the legacy osc[\u03b4/\u03b8/\u03b3] tracker. Quantifies how strongly\n# gamma-band envelope locks to theta-band phase \u2014 the canonical neural\n# correlate of feature binding (Lisman 2013).\n\nexport equation pac_bandpass_analytic {\n    # Hilbert-style band-limited analytic signal via FFT mask.\n    params: [x, f_lo, f_hi],\n    formula: \"z = ifft( fft(x) * H_analytic * mask(f_lo, f_hi) )\"\n}\n\nexport equation pac_phase_and_amplitude {\n    # Instantaneous phase from theta-band z_\u03b8; amplitude from |z_\u03b3|.\n    params: [z_theta, z_gamma],\n    formula: \"(phi_t, A_t) = (atan2(Im(z_theta), Re(z_theta)), |z_gamma|)\"\n}\n\nexport equation pac_modulation_index {\n    # Tort MI: KL divergence between phase-binned amplitude distribution\n    # and the uniform, normalised to [0, 1]. P_j = mean A in phase bin j.\n    params: [P, n_bins],\n    formula: \"PAC = (log(n_bins) - H(P)) / log(n_bins)\"\n}\n\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# FORMAL SPECIFICATIONS \u2014 analyser hints\n# \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n\nformal_spec emergent_telemetry_purity {\n    statement: \"C1-C6 mechanisms do not contribute to the trunk's gradient in this phase\",\n    proof_hint: \"All probes operate on .detach()'ed activations; PC predictor params are observer-local; no aux loss is registered\"\n}\n\nformal_spec topological_charge_integer_plateaus {\n    statement: \"Q is invariant to smooth deformations and changes only when a wall is crossed\",\n    proof_hint: \"Discrete analog of the Pontryagin index: Q \u2208 Z for closed loops; wall crossings are the only sources of \u00b11 jumps\"\n}\n\nformal_spec emergent_baseline_recovery {\n    statement: \"Each driven NT channel relaxes to its baseline when its driver is silent\",\n    proof_hint: \"DrivenNTSystem.step_full with None drivers applies a 0.05 exponential relaxation toward baselines per channel\"\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/lib/emergent"
    },
    "@brian/features/hyperbolic_attention": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\lib\\features\\hyperbolic_attention.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Hyperbolic (Poincar\u00e9-disc) multi-head attention \u2014 wiring spec.\n#\n# Imports the canonical equation from @brian/equations, binds it to the\n# Python implementation class, and exposes one wiring endpoint\n# (`edge`, kind=\"edge\") so a synapse can route its transmission through\n# this feature with `feature: \"hyperbolic_attention.edge\"`.\n#\n# This file declares the feature; it does NOT enable it. Activation is\n# per-architecture: an arch.neuro that wants hyperbolic attention\n# imports the feature and sets `active: true` in its own re-declaration\n# (or overrides via experiment harness). The default below is `false` so\n# any arch importing this is opt-in.\n#\n# References:\n#   * Ganea, B\u00e9cigneul, Hofmann \u2014 \"Hyperbolic Neural Networks\"\n#     (NeurIPS 2018) \u2014 the M\u00f6bius gyrovector formulation.\n#   * Ungar 2005 \u2014 Poincar\u00e9 ball M\u00f6bius operations.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/hyperbolic_attention.py\n# Contracts:      tests/test_hyperbolic_attention.py\n# Docs:           docs/features/hyperbolic_attention.md\n\nimport { hyperbolic_attention_eq } from \"@brian/equations\"\n\nexport feature hyperbolic_attention {\n    equation: hyperbolic_attention_eq,\n    active:   false,\n    impl:     \"neuroslm.modules.hyperbolic_attention.HyperbolicMultiHeadAttention\",\n\n    # Feature-level defaults; an arch may override these in its own\n    # `feature hyperbolic_attention { params: { ... } }` re-declaration.\n    # `d_model: d_sem` is a bare-identifier reference \u2014 codegen emits it\n    # unquoted so the impl receives the runtime trunk width.\n    params: {\n        d_model: d_sem,\n        n_heads: 4,\n        c:       1.0\n    },\n\n    # Wiring surfaces. A synapse references one of these via\n    # `feature: \"hyperbolic_attention.<endpoint>\"`.\n    endpoints: {\n        # Synapse-shaped: takes the pre-population's activations and\n        # produces the post-population's contribution.\n        edge: {\n            kind:   \"edge\",\n            inputs: [x_pre],\n            output: y\n        }\n    }\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@brian/features/hyperbolic_attention"
    },
    "@brian/features/rope_torus": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\lib\\features\\rope_torus.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# RoPE-on-a-Torus \u2014 wiring spec.\n#\n# Multi-frequency rotary positional encoding on the product manifold\n# T^n = (S^1)^n. Each 2D embedding slice rotates by an angle whose\n# period is drawn from a configurable schedule; positions wrap mod\n# each period (the \"torus\" part).\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/rope_torus.py\n# Contracts:      tests/test_rope_torus.py (19)\n# Docs:           docs/features/rope_torus.md\n\nimport { rope_torus_eq } from \"@brian/equations\"\n\nexport feature rope_torus {\n    equation: rope_torus_eq,\n    active:   false,\n    impl:     \"neuroslm.modules.rope_torus.RoPETorus\",\n\n    # \u2500\u2500 Per-arch defaults; override in arch.neuro's re-declaration. \u2500\u2500\n    # `d_model: d_sem` is a bare-identifier reference \u2014 codegen emits it\n    # unquoted so the cos/sin tables track the runtime trunk width.\n    # max_seq_len caps the precomputed cos/sin table \u2014 longer seqs are\n    # recomputed on the fly (cheap, ~T\u00b7d_pair flops).\n    params: {\n        d_model:           d_sem,\n        max_seq_len:       2048,\n        base:              10000.0,\n        schedule:          \"geometric\",\n        learnable_periods: false\n    },\n\n    endpoints: {\n        edge: {\n            kind:   \"edge\",\n            inputs: [x_pre],\n            output: y\n        }\n    }\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@brian/features/rope_torus"
    },
    "@brian/features/hrr_memory": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\lib\\features\\hrr_memory.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# HRR (Holographic Reduced Representations) memory \u2014 wiring spec.\n#\n# Self-attention-shaped HRR memory: each token projects to (k, v, q);\n# the per-batch memory M = \u03a3_t bind(k_t, v_t) is queried via\n# unbind(M, q_x). Cost O(T \u00b7 d_memory \u00b7 log d_memory) \u2014 far below\n# attention's O(T\u00b2 \u00b7 d).\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/hrr_memory.py\n# Contracts:      tests/test_hrr_memory.py (16)\n# Docs:           docs/features/hrr_memory.md\n\nimport { hrr_memory_eq } from \"@brian/equations\"\n\nexport feature hrr_memory {\n    equation: hrr_memory_eq,\n    active:   false,\n    impl:     \"neuroslm.modules.hrr_memory.HRRMemory\",\n\n    # `d_model: d_sem` ties the projection width to the runtime trunk\n    # dim; `d_memory` is independent and stays an integer literal.\n    params: {\n        d_model:        d_sem,\n        d_memory:       512,\n        normalize_keys: true,\n        bias:           true\n    },\n\n    endpoints: {\n        edge: {\n            kind:   \"edge\",\n            inputs: [x_pre],\n            output: y\n        }\n    }\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@brian/features/hrr_memory"
    },
    "@brian/features/predictive_coding_residual": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\lib\\features\\predictive_coding_residual.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Predictive-coding residuals (Rao-Ballard 1999) \u2014 wiring spec.\n#\n# Self-predicting variant: forward(x) computes the residual \u03b5 = x - g(x)\n# against a learned predictor g, returns x - \u03b1\u00b7\u03b5. Residual norm exposed\n# via the module's `last_residual_norm` buffer for downstream losses.\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/predictive_coding_residual.py\n# Contracts:      tests/test_predictive_coding_residual.py (14)\n# Docs:           docs/features/predictive_coding_residual.md\n\nimport { predictive_coding_residual_eq } from \"@brian/equations\"\n\nexport feature predictive_coding_residual {\n    equation: predictive_coding_residual_eq,\n    active:   false,\n    impl:     \"neuroslm.modules.predictive_coding_residual.PredictiveCodingResidual\",\n\n    # `d_model: d_sem` ties the predictor's hidden width to the runtime\n    # trunk dim. step_size, mode, and n_iterations are independent.\n    params: {\n        d_model:      d_sem,\n        step_size:    0.1,\n        mode:         \"single\",\n        n_iterations: 1\n    },\n\n    endpoints: {\n        edge: {\n            kind:   \"edge\",\n            inputs: [x_pre],\n            output: y\n        }\n    }\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@brian/features/predictive_coding_residual"
    },
    "@brian/features/surprise_gated_moe": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\lib\\features\\surprise_gated_moe.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Surprise-gated Mixture-of-Experts \u2014 wiring spec.\n#\n# Standard MoE (Shazeer 2017) extended with dynamic per-token top-k:\n# k(x) = round(k_min + (k_max-k_min)\u00b7\u03c3(steepness\u00b7(surprise - midpoint))).\n# Internal surprise = normalised gating-distribution entropy (low =\n# confident routing, high = uncertain \u2192 more experts).\n#\n# Implementation: neuroslm/modules/surprise_gated_moe.py\n# Contracts:      tests/test_surprise_gated_moe.py (20)\n# Docs:           docs/features/surprise_gated_moe.md\n\nimport { surprise_gated_moe_eq } from \"@brian/equations\"\n\nexport feature surprise_gated_moe {\n    equation: surprise_gated_moe_eq,\n    active:   false,\n    impl:     \"neuroslm.modules.surprise_gated_moe.SurpriseGatedMoE\",\n\n    # `d_model: d_sem` ties expert in/out widths to the runtime trunk\n    # dim. d_hidden, n_experts, k_min/k_max, etc. stay literals.\n    params: {\n        d_model:             d_sem,\n        n_experts:           8,\n        d_hidden:            1024,\n        k_min:               1,\n        k_max:               4,\n        midpoint:            1.0,\n        steepness:           4.0,\n        load_balance_weight: 0.01\n    },\n\n    endpoints: {\n        edge: {\n            kind:   \"edge\",\n            inputs: [x_pre],\n            output: y\n        }\n    }\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@brian/features/surprise_gated_moe"
    },
    "@/modules/sensory": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\sensory.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 0 \u2014 Sensory input + association cortex\n#\n# Both are rate-coded populations: their output is a thresholded view of\n# the input (no recurrence, no state). The canonical algebraic equation\n# `y = ReLU(x)` makes this explicit. Adjust here without touching arch.neuro.\n\nexport population sensory {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.005,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population association {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/sensory"
    },
    "@/modules/thalamus": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\thalamus.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 1 \u2014 Thalamic relay (bowtie bottleneck entry)\n#\n# Gated dynamics: ReLU input modulated by a learnable scalar gate. The\n# gate parameter (zero-initialised) is the sigmoid-bounded \"openness\" of\n# the relay. With gate=0, output is zero \u2014 nothing passes through.\n\nexport population thalamus {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"gated\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x) * sigmoid(gate)\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/thalamus"
    },
    "@/modules/world": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\world.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 2 \u2014 Predictive state models\n#\n# World model (external state) and self model (internal state). Both\n# rate-coded with slow timescales (50ms) \u2014 they accumulate predictions\n# rather than respond to immediate input.\n\nexport population world {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.05,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population self_m {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.05,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/world"
    },
    "@/modules/amygdala": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\amygdala.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 3 \u2014 Subcortical affect (emotion/salience)\n#\n# Amygdala: integrate-and-fire neurons \u2014 the only ODE-driven population\n# in the architecture. Membrane potential V decays toward input current,\n# with time constant tau. Spiking events (threshold + reset) are a\n# Stage-3 Brian2-grammar feature; for now this is a sub-threshold leaky\n# integrator.\n#\n# Insula: rate-coded interoceptive signal at 20ms timescale.\n\nexport population amygdala {\n    count: 32,\n    dynamics: \"integrate_and_fire\",\n    ode: \"dV/dt = (-V + x) / tau\",\n    timescale: 0.005,\n    capacity: 0.5\n}\n\nexport population insula {\n    count: 64,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/amygdala"
    },
    "@/modules/qualia": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\qualia.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 4 \u2014 Qualia state (subjective experience encoding)\n#\n# Rate-coded subjective state. Receives binding from multiple upstream\n# regions (qualia warp depends on insula's interoceptive signal, etc.);\n# the wiring lives in arch.neuro.\n\nexport population qualia {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/qualia"
    },
    "@/modules/gws": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\gws.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 5 \u2014 Global Workspace (conscious access bottleneck)\n#\n# GWS is the narrowest bowtie bottleneck. Winner-take-all sparsifies the\n# input via low-temperature softmax: a single dominant signal wins, the\n# rest get suppressed. Effective \"ignition\" gate of conscious broadcast.\n#   y = softmax(x / 0.1) * d_sem   \u2014 temperature 0.1, scaled by d_sem\n#\n# Neural geometry: identity passthrough that distributes the geometric\n# embedding alongside the GWS output (for downstream consumers that care\n# about the structural form of the workspace state).\n\nexport population gws {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"winner_take_all\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x / 0.1) * d_sem\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 8.0\n}\n\nexport population neural_geometry {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"static\",\n    equation: \"y = x\",\n    timescale: 0.001,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/gws"
    },
    "@/modules/hippocampus": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\hippocampus.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 6 \u2014 Memory: storage & consolidation\n#\n# Hippocampus: attractor network with leak rate alpha=0.1. New input\n# decays the persistent state s toward the input pattern:\n#   y = (1-alpha) * s + alpha * ReLU(x)\n# (Pattern-completion semantics \u2014 partial cues retrieve full memories.)\n#\n# Entorhinal: rate-coded indexing/binding layer between hippocampus and\n# cortex.\n#\n# Cerebellum: rate-coded predictive error signal (very fast, 5ms).\n\nexport population hippo {\n    count: 4096,\n    dynamics: \"attractor_network\",\n    equation: \"y = (1 - alpha) * s + alpha * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.1,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population entorhinal {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.05,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population cerebellum {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.005,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/hippocampus"
    },
    "@/modules/pfc": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\pfc.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 7 \u2014 Cognitive control: PFC + ACC\n#\n# Prefrontal cortex (PFC): conflict monitoring, planning, top-down bias.\n# Anterior cingulate (ACC): error monitoring, attention allocation.\n# Both rate-coded at 20ms timescale. NT modulation (DA/5HT/ACh/GABA on\n# PFC; DA on ACC) is wired in arch.neuro.\n\nexport population pfc {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population acc {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/pfc"
    },
    "@/modules/bg": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\bg.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 8 \u2014 Executive: action selection + learning\n#\n# Basal ganglia (BG): another winner-take-all, this time over a discrete\n# action lattice (capacity 4). softmax temperature 0.1 keeps the\n# selection sharp.\n#\n# Forward model: predicted next-state representation, rate-coded.\n# Evaluator: scalar value estimate for the current action; rate-coded\n# fast (10ms) for tight RPE timing.\n\nexport population bg {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"winner_take_all\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x / 0.1) * d_sem\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n\nexport population forward_m {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population evaluator {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/bg"
    },
    "@/modules/dmn": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\dmn.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 9 \u2014 Consciousness: narrative + metacognition\n#\n# DMN (default mode network): rate-coded narrative aggregator. Slow\n# (100ms) \u2014 accumulates over many cognitive cycles. NT modulation by\n# 5HT (dampens introspection) and ACh (attention) is wired in arch.neuro.\n#\n# Thought transformer: attention-pool dynamics \u2014 weighted softmax of the\n# input with itself as the value, yielding `softmax(x) * ReLU(x)`. Mimics\n# a single self-attention head over the cognitive stream.\n#\n# Claustrum: gated relay that synchronises cortical activity. Same\n# `gated` dynamics as the thalamus.\n\nexport population dmn {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.1,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population thought_transformer {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"attention_pool\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x) * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n\nexport population claustrum {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"gated\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x) * sigmoid(gate)\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 2.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/dmn"
    },
    "@/modules/motor": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\motor.neuro",
     "source": "# Stage 10 \u2014 Motor output\n#\n# Final rate-coded layer driving action execution. Fast timescale (5ms)\n# so motor commands can change on tight loops.\n\nexport population motor {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.005,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/motor"
    },
    "@/modules/nuclei": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\nuclei.neuro",
     "source": "# Neuromodulatory nuclei (NT source populations)\n#\n# These are the brainstem/midbrain nuclei whose activity sets the global\n# NT concentrations the arch.neuro modulations consume:\n#   VTA, SN     \u2192 dopamine\n#   LC          \u2192 norepinephrine\n#   Raphe       \u2192 serotonin\n#   NBM         \u2192 acetylcholine\n#   NAcc        \u2192 DA gating (downstream target)\n#\n# All are rate-coded \u2014 these populations represent *firing rates* of the\n# corresponding nucleus, and downstream NT concentration is driven by\n# them via the kinetics declared in the neurotransmitter blocks\n# (arch.neuro).\n\nexport population vta {\n    count: 64,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population nucleus_accumbens {\n    count: 64,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population locus_coeruleus {\n    count: 32,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population raphe_nuclei {\n    count: 48,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.05,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population nucleus_basalis {\n    count: 32,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n\nexport population substantia_nigra {\n    count: 64,\n    dynamics: \"rate_code\",\n    equation: \"y = ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.01,\n    capacity: 1.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/nuclei"
    },
    "@/modules/reasoning_cortex": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\reasoning_cortex.neuro",
     "source": "# Reasoning Cortex \u2014 parallel structured-reasoning lane\n#\n# Added with the stacked-OOD topology (synapses pfc -> reasoning_cortex ->\n# motor and reasoning_cortex <-> dmn lateral GABA inhibition in arch.neuro).\n# Acts as a MoE-style specialised lane: when DMN's narrative drive is\n# suppressed by reasoning_cortex via GABA, the trunk routes through this\n# structured lane instead of the default-mode narrative path. The reverse\n# inhibition (DMN -> reasoning_cortex) prevents both from firing\n# simultaneously \u2014 classic sparse-coding / one-expert-per-token effect.\n\nexport population reasoning_cortex {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"attention_pool\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x) * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/reasoning_cortex"
    },
    "@/modules/cortex_specialists": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\modules\\cortex_specialists.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Multi-Trunk-v2 specialist language cortices\n#\n# Four specialist cortical populations that form the trunk of the\n# multi-cortex thalamic ensemble (see `neuroslm/cortex.py` for the\n# Python lowering and `tests/test_ensemble_routing.py` for the TDD\n# acceptance suite).  At the DSL level each cortex is declared as an\n# `attention_pool` population \u2014 the same dynamics as `reasoning_cortex`,\n# so they slot into the existing trunk topology without disturbing the\n# bowtie or `param_scope trunk` gradient flow.\n#\n# The Python `ThalamicRouter` (lexical-bias prior + zero-init learnable\n# head + optional BEMA biological damping) realises the per-token\n# mixture weights p_{ti} on the probability simplex Delta^N, where N is\n# the number of cortices declared here.  The DSL declarations below\n# tell the analyser / linter / `brian bundle` that these populations\n# *exist* and participate in the trunk gradient scope; the per-token\n# routing maths lives in Python (the DSL `synapse a -> b` form is\n# one-to-one and cannot express the dynamic 4-way fan-out directly).\n#\n# Mathematical model (per token t in batch sample i, N = #cortices):\n#\n#     L_{ti}  =  beta * 1[x_{ti} in D]  +  W @ phi(x_{ti})       # router logits\n#     p_{ti}  =  softmax(L_{ti})                                  # weights in Delta^N\n#     h_{ti}  =  sum_n p_{ti,n} * P_n( C_n(x) )_{ti}              # mixed hidden\n#\n# where C_n is the n-th specialist cortex (this file's populations),\n# P_n the per-cortex projection to the shared d_target, beta the\n# `lexical_bias_weight` (default 2.0), and W the zero-init learnable\n# router head.  See `training { multi_cortex { ... } }` in\n# `arch.neuro` for the hyperparameter exposure, and Section 5.7 of\n# `docs/architecture.md` for the full Phi-maximisation derivation.\n#\n# Default domain assignment (mirrors `neuroslm.cortex.DEFAULT_GPT2_VARIANTS`):\n#\n#     cortex_math     -> gpt2-medium  (stand-in for DeepSeek-Math in prod)\n#     cortex_code     -> distilgpt2   (stand-in for a code fine-tune)\n#     cortex_chat     -> gpt2         (stand-in for DialoGPT)\n#     cortex_general  -> gpt2         (balanced LM baseline)\n#\n# References:\n#   - Sherman & Guillery (2002), Phil. Trans. R. Soc. \u2014 Thalamus as relay\n#   - Halassa & Kastner (2017), Nat. Neurosci. \u2014 Thalamic cortical control\n#   - Shazeer et al. (2017), arXiv:1701.06538 \u2014 Sparsely-gated MoE\n#   - Fedus et al. (2022), JMLR \u2014 Switch Transformer\n\nexport population cortex_math {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"attention_pool\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x) * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n\nexport population cortex_code {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"attention_pool\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x) * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n\nexport population cortex_chat {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"attention_pool\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x) * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n\nexport population cortex_general {\n    count: 256,\n    dynamics: \"attention_pool\",\n    equation: \"y = softmax(x) * ReLU(x)\",\n    timescale: 0.02,\n    capacity: 4.0\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/modules/cortex_specialists"
    },
    "@/lib/constraints": {
     "path": "C:\\Users\\morrossl\\Documents\\Private\\SLM\\architectures\\rcc_bowtie\\lib\\constraints.neuro",
     "source": "# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# lib/constraints.neuro \u2014 math-first formal constraint systems\n#\n# Three core constraint systems that govern the RCC Bowtie topology and ensure\n# biological plausibility + integrated information. These are the *canonical*\n# mathematical specifications; the harness applies them as invariants during\n# forward pass and gradient computation.\n#\n# Constraints are verified at compile time and enforced at runtime via\n# auxiliary losses and post-hoc corrections (see neuroslm/dsl/constraints.py).\n\n# =============================================================================\n# 1. NARRATIVE CONSISTENCY SHEAF \u2014 \u03a6 > 0 at narrative layer\n# =============================================================================\n#\n# A narrative is \"consistent\" if its claims (as encoded by the DMN at each\n# step) satisfy a local cohomology constraint: the contradiction measure\n# between consecutive narrative states must remain below a threshold, OR the\n# system explicitly resolves contradictions via the PFC.\n#\n# Mathematical form (singular homology of narrative transitions):\n#   For each narrative claim c_i \u2208 narrative_state_i,\n#   Contradiction(c_i, c_{i+1}) = <c_i, c_{i+1}> (cosine similarity negated)\n#   \u2265 (1 - contradiction_threshold)  \u27f9  valid transition\n#   < (1 - contradiction_threshold)  \u27f9  PFC must resolve (explicit cost)\n#\n# Mechanism (h1_cohomology_proxy):\n#   Track the \"coherence kernel\" \u2014 the intersection of all narrative claims\n#   across the last H steps. If it shrinks (claims become mutually\n#   inconsistent), trigger a PFC-mediated resolution phase. This is a proxy\n#   for Mayer Vietoris cohomology in the narrative sheaf.\n\nexport sheaf sheaf_narrative_consistency {\n    rule: \"h1_cohomology_proxy\",\n    contradiction_threshold: 0.7,\n\n    # Formal definition: narrative transitions must stay coherent\n    claims_divergence: {\n        formula: \"D_t = mean(1 - cosine_similarity(narrative_t, narrative_{t-1}))\",\n        penalty: \"\u03bb_narr * max(0, D_t - contradiction_threshold)^2\"\n    },\n\n    # PFC resolution cost (forced re-planning when narrative incoherent)\n    pfc_resolution_cost: {\n        formula: \"C_pfc = \u03bb_pfc * divergence_phase_indicator\",\n        active_when: \"D_t > contradiction_threshold\"\n    },\n\n    # Integration: narrative is integrated (\u03a6 > 0) iff it's both:\n    #   - coherent with its own history (D_t < threshold)\n    #   - causally influences the next decision (gradient flows from DMN \u2192 PFC)\n    integration_penalty: {\n        formula: \"\u03a6_narrative = <DMN_out, PFC_in>\",\n        constraint: \"\u03a6_narrative > 0.1\"  # integrate: minimum causal influence\n    }\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# 2. INTEGRATED INFORMATION METRIC (\u03a6) \u2014 Tononi 4.0 formalism\n# =============================================================================\n#\n# The entire architecture is designed to maximize Integrated Information (\u03a6)\n# per Tononi (2016) + Mashour (2020). This constraint ensures that the system\n# is irreducible: no proper subset of the brain can account for the full\n# behavior.\n#\n# Mathematical form (geometric IIT 4.0):\n#   \u03a6 = H(partition_1) + H(partition_2) - H(whole)\n#   where H is the stochastic complexity (causal density in the manifest graph)\n#\n# Operationalization (tractable proxy):\n#   1. Count the number of cross-module synapses with non-zero gradient\n#   2. Measure the rank of the Jacobian at the bowtie point\n#   3. Ensure both are high (wide bottleneck \u2192 high \u03a6)\n#\n# The architecture is explicitly designed to maximize \u03a6:\n#   - Thalamus (bowtie input)   \u2190 sensory, PFC re-entry\n#   - GWS (bowtie point)        \u2190 thalamus, state models, narrative, learning\n#   - Downstream (bowtie output) \u2190 GWS diverges to hippocampus, PFC, DMN, motor\n# The bowtie structure prevents any subset from being independent: all pathways\n# pass through the narrow point.\n\nexport formal_spec formal_phi_integration {\n    rule: \"integrated_information\",\n    metric: \"phi\",\n\n    # Measure 1: Non-zero gradient paths (each path = a degree of freedom)\n    causal_density: {\n        formula: \"paths_active = count(|\u2207 synaptic_weight| > \u03b5)\",\n        target: \"paths_active > 80% of total synapses\"  # most pathways active\n    },\n\n    # Measure 2: Jacobian rank at bowtie (GWS is the critical point)\n    bowtie_rank: {\n        formula: \"J_GWS = \u2202(GWS_out) / \u2202(GWS_in)\",\n        target: \"rank(J_GWS) \u2265 0.8 * min(d_GWS_in, d_GWS_out)\"\n    },\n\n    # Measure 3: Information loss across bowtie (the narrowing effect)\n    # If the bowtie is too narrow, information is lost \u2192 low \u03a6.\n    # If the bowtie is too wide, there's no bottleneck \u2192 low \u03a6.\n    bowtie_information_loss: {\n        formula: \"IL = H(input) - H(output) at bowtie point\",\n        target: \"0.1 < IL < 0.5\"  # balanced: narrow but not lossy\n    },\n\n    # Constraint: the system must be irreducible\n    # No single module can account for the behavior; all are needed.\n    irreducibility_penalty: {\n        formula: \"\u03a6_system = I_max - I_partition_max\",\n        where: [\n            \"I_max = mutual_information(input, output)\",\n            \"I_partition_max = max over all bipartitions of I_part\"\n        ],\n        constraint: \"\u03a6_system > 0.2\"\n    }\n}\n\n# =============================================================================\n# 3. BOWTIE TOPOLOGY STRUCTURAL CONSTRAINT \u2014 narrowing-widening form\n# =============================================================================\n#\n# The RCC Bowtie is not just a description; it's a hard constraint on the\n# network topology. The constraint is enforced at compile time (checked by\n# the linter) and at runtime (auxiliary loss if the gradient tries to \"bypass\"\n# the bowtie).\n#\n# Mathematical form (graph-theoretic constraint):\n#   1. Narrowing: All sensory pathways (raw input) must converge to a set of\n#      \"bowtie input\" populations (thalamus, association).\n#   2. Widening: The GWS (bowtie point, ~256d) must diverge to >= 6 downstream\n#      regions (hippocampus, PFC, DMN, basal ganglia, motor, learning).\n#   3. Re-entry: At least one downstream region (PFC) must send a feedback\n#      synapse back to the bowtie input (thalamus) to close the loop.\n#   4. No shortcuts: There are no direct synapses from sensory to basal ganglia,\n#      motor, or output. All action must be routed through planning (PFC).\n#   5. Gradual degradation: Removing any single downstream region reduces\n#      performance, but removing the bowtie point makes performance collapse.\n#\n# The constraint ensures:\n#   - Biological realism (matches mammalian anatomy)\n#   - Integrated information (\u03a6 > 0 only if the bowtie is intact)\n#   - Reasoning bottleneck (all high-level decisions pass through PFC)\n\nexport formal_spec formal_bowtie_topology {\n    rule: \"narrowing_widening\",\n    metric: \"structural_constraint\",\n\n    # Requirement 1: Narrowing phase (all sensory \u2192 bowtie input)\n    narrowing_phase: {\n        bowtie_inputs: [\"thalamus\", \"association\"],\n        constraint: \"All sensory synapses must target one of bowtie_inputs\",\n        verification: \"linter checks: sensory -> (thalamus | association) only\"\n    },\n\n    # Requirement 2: Widening phase (bowtie point \u2192 downstream)\n    widening_phase: {\n        bowtie_point: \"gws\",  # Global Workspace\n        downstream_regions: [\"hippo\", \"pfc\", \"dmn\", \"bg\", \"motor\", \"reasoning_cortex\"],\n        constraint: \"GWS must broadcast to \u2265 5 distinct downstream regions\",\n        penalty: \"\u03bb_bowtie * (6 - num_downstream_with_non_zero_grad)^2\"\n    },\n\n    # Requirement 3: Re-entry (closure \u2192 \u03a6 > 0)\n    closure_reentry: {\n        formula: \"re-entry pathways = pfc \u2192 thalamus, motor \u2192 sensory\",\n        constraint: \"Both re-entry synapses must have |weight| > 0.1 at test time\",\n        penalty: \"\u03bb_reentry * (1 - tanh(10 * |reentry_weight|))\"\n    },\n\n    # Requirement 4: No shortcuts (structural integrity)\n    no_shortcuts: {\n        forbidden_paths: [\n            \"sensory \u219b basal_ganglia (action selection MUST go PFC \u2192 BG)\",\n            \"sensory \u219b motor (movement MUST go PFC \u2192 Motor)\",\n            \"sensory \u219b output (response MUST go PFC \u2192 output)\"\n        ],\n        enforcement: \"linter error if forbidden paths exist; auto-fix: remove\"\n    },\n\n    # Requirement 5: Graceful degradation\n    degradation_constraint: {\n        formula: \"delta_loss(remove_region_i) > 0 for each downstream region\",\n        formula_bowtie: \"delta_loss(remove_gws) >> delta_loss(remove_region)\",\n        target: \"single region removal: +0.1\u20130.3 PPL; GWS removal: +5+ PPL\"\n    }\n}\n",
     "specifier": "@/lib/constraints"
    }
   },
